// Unit 18: Im Biergarten
// Level: B1

const UNIT_18 =
{n:18,lang:"de",srcLang:"en",track:"v2",title:"Im Biergarten",sub:"Beer garden, Spargelzeit, als vs wenn, fixed prepositions, da-/wo- compounds",icon:"\uD83C\uDF7A",level:"B1.2",color:"#7B5EE8",lessons:[

// ─── Lesson 1: Unter den Kastanien ───────────────────────────────────
{id:"deu_r18l1",title:"Unter den Kastanien",icon:"\uD83C\uDF33",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Unter den Kastanien",desc:"A Berlin Biergarten in late June. Golden light through chestnut leaves. Fairy lights, grilled sausages, clinking beer steins. Time to learn how Germans socialize outdoors.",goals:["Learn 18 restaurant and socializing words","Meet the full cast for a summer evening together","Express hunger, thirst, and satisfaction"]},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Terrasse",src:"the terrace, the patio",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"An outdoor dining area. Bierg\u00e4rten have their own tradition, but both mean eating outside.",example:"A: Sollen wir drinnen oder auf der Terrasse sitzen?\nB: Auf der Terrasse! Das Wetter ist perfekt.\nA: Gut, ich sehe noch einen freien Tisch.\nB: Schnell, bevor ihn jemand nimmt!",exampleSrc:"A: Should we sit inside or on the terrace?\nB: On the terrace! The weather is perfect.\nA: Good, I see a free table.\nB: Quick, before someone takes it!",funFact:"From French 'terrasse.' Germans flock outdoors the moment the sun appears. Bierg\u00e4rten technically have their own traditions separate from a Terrasse, but both mean eating outside."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Treffpunkt",src:"the meeting point",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"'Treff' (meeting) + 'Punkt' (point). Every friend group has one.",example:"A: Wo ist unser Treffpunkt heute?\nB: Im Biergarten, unter den Kastanien.\nA: Gut, ich bin in zehn Minuten da.\nB: Hildi wartet schon!",exampleSrc:"A: Where is our meeting point today?\nB: In the beer garden, under the chestnut trees.\nA: Good, I will be there in ten minutes.\nB: Hildi is already waiting!",funFact:"'Treff' (meeting) + 'Punkt' (point). Every German friend group has their Treffpunkt. The Biergarten in summer is the ultimate one."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Wirt",src:"the innkeeper, the landlord",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"From Old High German 'wirt' (host). Runs the whole Biergarten operation.",example:"A: Wer ist der Wirt hier?\nB: Der Mann mit der Sch\u00fcrze da dr\u00fcben.\nA: Er sieht freundlich aus.\nB: Ja, er kennt alle Stammg\u00e4ste beim Namen.",exampleSrc:"A: Who is the innkeeper here?\nB: The man with the apron over there.\nA: He looks friendly.\nB: Yes, he knows all the regulars by name.",funFact:"The pub landlord. From Old High German 'wirt' (host). A Biergartenwirt runs the whole operation. Related to English 'worth' through the idea of hospitality."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Wirtin",src:"the innkeeper (female)",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"The -in suffix marks feminine. Many famous Berlin Wirtinnen have run legendary beer gardens.",example:"A: Die Wirtin hat uns begr\u00fc\u00dft.\nB: Ja, sie ist hier seit zwanzig Jahren.\nA: Sie kennt wirklich jeden.\nB: Das macht einen guten Biergarten aus.",exampleSrc:"A: The innkeeper greeted us.\nB: Yes, she has been here for twenty years.\nA: She really knows everyone.\nB: That is what makes a good beer garden.",funFact:"Female innkeeper. The -in suffix. Many famous Berlin Wirtinnen have run legendary beer gardens for decades. 'Die Wirtin' is also the title of a famous German folk song."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Kellner",src:"the waiter",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"From 'Keller' (cellar). Originally the person who brought drinks up from the cellar.",example:"A: Wo ist unser Kellner?\nB: Ich glaube, er bedient den Tisch da dr\u00fcben.\nA: Wir warten schon zehn Minuten.\nB: Im Biergarten muss man geduldig sein.",exampleSrc:"A: Where is our waiter?\nB: I think he is serving the table over there.\nA: We have been waiting ten minutes.\nB: In a beer garden you have to be patient.",funFact:"From 'Keller' (cellar). A waiter was originally the person who brought drinks up from the cellar. In Bavaria, you might hear 'Bedienung!' (Service!) instead of calling the Kellner."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"der Treffpunkt",src:"the meeting point"},{trg:"der Wirt",src:"the innkeeper, the landlord"},{trg:"die Wirtin",src:"the innkeeper (female)"},{trg:"der Kellner",src:"the waiter"}]},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Kellnerin",src:"the waitress",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Female server. In a traditional Biergarten, she carries multiple one-liter beer steins at once.",example:"A: Die Kellnerin ist unglaublich schnell.\nB: Siehst du, wie viele Bierkr\u00fcge sie tr\u00e4gt?\nA: Vier auf einmal!\nB: Das ist noch gar nichts f\u00fcr einen Biergarten.",exampleSrc:"A: The waitress is incredibly fast.\nB: Do you see how many beer steins she is carrying?\nA: Four at once!\nB: That is nothing for a beer garden.",funFact:"Female server. In a traditional Biergarten, the Kellnerin carries multiple one-liter beer steins at once. The record is 29 steins carried at once by a Bavarian Kellnerin."},
{type:"mc",q:"Wo treffen sich die Freunde heute Abend?",opts:["auf der gemütlichen Terrasse","am Treffpunkt im Biergarten","direkt beim Wirt zu Hause","in der kleinen Kantine"],ans:"am Treffpunkt im Biergarten",hint:"Treff (meeting) + Punkt (point). The agreed location where the group gathers."},
{type:"fb",s:"Die {1} hat uns freundlich begr\u00fc\u00dft. Sie ist hier seit zwanzig Jahren.",a:["Wirtin"],opts:["Wirtin","Kellnerin","Terrasse","Mahlzeit"],hint:"Which feminine noun means a female innkeeper who runs the beer garden?",sSrc:"The innkeeper greeted us warmly. She has been here for twenty years."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Ober",src:"the waiter (formal)",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Short for 'Oberkellner' (head waiter). An older, more formal word.",example:"A: Herr Ober, die Speisekarte bitte!\nB: Sofort, mein Herr.\nA: Und bringen Sie bitte auch Wasser.\nB: Nat\u00fcrlich, stilles oder mit Kohlens\u00e4ure?",exampleSrc:"A: Waiter, the menu please!\nB: Right away, sir.\nA: And please bring water too.\nB: Of course, still or sparkling?",funFact:"Short for 'Oberkellner' (head waiter). An older, more formal word. 'Herr Ober!' is how you call a waiter in a traditional Austrian or South German restaurant."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Trinkgeld",src:"the tip",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"'Trink' (drink) + 'Geld' (money). In Germany, tipping is 5-10%.",example:"A: Wie viel Trinkgeld gibt man in Deutschland?\nB: Normalerweise f\u00fcnf bis zehn Prozent.\nA: Das ist weniger als in Amerika.\nB: Ja, aber Kellner verdienen hier mehr Grundgehalt.",exampleSrc:"A: How much tip do you give in Germany?\nB: Usually five to ten percent.\nA: That is less than in America.\nB: Yes, but waiters earn more base salary here.",funFact:"'Trink' (drink) + 'Geld' (money). Tip money was originally money so the server could buy themselves a drink. In Germany, tipping is 5-10%, not the 15-20% common in the US."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Grill",src:"the grill, the barbecue",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Same word as English. Germans grill obsessively in summer.",example:"A: Riechst du den Grill?\nB: Ja, Bratwurst und Steaks!\nA: Ich will auch etwas vom Grill.\nB: Dann gehen wir zur Grillstation.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you smell the grill?\nB: Yes, bratwurst and steaks!\nA: I want something from the grill too.\nB: Then let us go to the grill station.",funFact:"Same word as English. Germans grill obsessively in summer. 'Grillen' (to barbecue) is practically a national sport. A Biergarten often has a Grillstation with Bratwurst and Steaks."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Scheibe",src:"the slice, the disk, the pane",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Anything flat and round or flat and thin. 'Eine Scheibe Brot' = a slice of bread.",example:"A: M\u00f6chtest du eine Scheibe Brot?\nB: Ja, bitte, mit Butter.\nA: Und eine Scheibe K\u00e4se dazu?\nB: Perfekt, danke!",exampleSrc:"A: Would you like a slice of bread?\nB: Yes, please, with butter.\nA: And a slice of cheese with it?\nB: Perfect, thanks!",funFact:"A slice, disk, or pane. 'Eine Scheibe Brot' (a slice of bread). Also 'Windschutzscheibe' (windshield). The word covers anything flat and round or flat and thin."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Mahlzeit",src:"the meal, the mealtime",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"'Mahl' (meal) + 'Zeit' (time). Also a noon greeting among coworkers.",example:"A: Mahlzeit!\nB: Mahlzeit! Gehst du auch in die Kantine?\nA: Ja, ich brauche eine warme Mahlzeit.\nB: Ich auch. Heute gibt es Schnitzel.",exampleSrc:"A: Bon appetit! (noon greeting)\nB: Bon appetit! Are you going to the cafeteria too?\nA: Yes, I need a warm meal.\nB: Me too. Today they have schnitzel.",funFact:"'Mahl' (meal) + 'Zeit' (time). Also a greeting: saying 'Mahlzeit!' around noon is how German coworkers greet each other at lunch. It is simultaneously a word and a social ritual."},
{type:"fb",s:"Wie viel {1} gibt man in Deutschland? -- F\u00fcnf bis zehn Prozent.",a:["Trinkgeld"],opts:["Trinkgeld","Grill","Scheibe","Mahlzeit"],hint:"Which neuter noun describes the small extra payment left on the table at the end of a meal to thank the server?",sSrc:"How much tip do you give in Germany? -- Five to ten percent."}
]},
{id:"deu_r18l1b",title:"Unter den Kastanien (Teil 2)",icon:"\uD83C\uDF33",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Unter den Kastanien (continued)",desc:"Continue practicing the vocabulary from this topic.",goals:["Review and practice key words"]},
{type:"mc",q:"Wer bringt die Getr\u00e4nke? Urspr\u00fcnglich holte er sie aus dem Keller. Wer ist er?",opts:["der Kellner","der zufriedene Ober","der bekannte Wirt","die freundliche Wirtin"],ans:"der Kellner",hint:"From 'Keller' (cellar). Originally the person who brought drinks up from below."},
{type:"teach",trg:"gem\u00fctlich",src:"cozy, comfortable, convivial",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Possibly the most untranslatable German word. No single English word captures it.",example:"A: Der Biergarten ist wirklich gem\u00fctlich.\nB: Ja, die Lichterketten machen alles so sch\u00f6n.\nA: Und die alten Kastanienb\u00e4ume.\nB: Das ist typisch deutsch: Gem\u00fctlichkeit im Freien.",exampleSrc:"A: The beer garden is really cozy.\nB: Yes, the fairy lights make everything so pretty.\nA: And the old chestnut trees.\nB: That is typically German: coziness outdoors.",funFact:"Possibly the most untranslatable German word. Cozy, comfortable, convivial, warm, relaxed. A Biergarten under chestnut trees on a summer evening is the definition of gem\u00fctlich. No single English word captures it."},
{type:"teach",trg:"durstig",src:"thirsty",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"From 'Durst' (thirst). The -ig suffix turns nouns into adjectives.",example:"A: Bist du durstig?\nB: Ja, sehr! Ich brauche ein gro\u00dfes Bier.\nA: Oder ein Wasser?\nB: Erst das Bier, dann das Wasser.",exampleSrc:"A: Are you thirsty?\nB: Yes, very! I need a big beer.\nA: Or a water?\nB: First the beer, then the water.",funFact:"From 'Durst' (thirst). 'Ich bin durstig' is survival vocabulary in any Biergarten. The -ig suffix turns nouns into adjectives: Durst becomes durstig, Hunger becomes hungrig."},
{type:"teach",trg:"hungrig",src:"hungry",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"From 'Hunger.' Same pattern as durstig. Cognate with English 'hungry.'",example:"A: Ich bin so hungrig!\nB: Wollen wir etwas bestellen?\nA: Ja, sofort. Eine Bratwurst vom Grill.\nB: Und Kartoffelsalat dazu.",exampleSrc:"A: I am so hungry!\nB: Shall we order something?\nA: Yes, right away. A bratwurst from the grill.\nB: And potato salad with it.",funFact:"From 'Hunger.' Same pattern as durstig. 'Bist du hungrig?' is the question that starts every Biergarten evening. Cognate with English 'hungry.'"},
{type:"teach",trg:"satt",src:"full, satisfied (after eating)",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"'Ich bin satt' = I have had enough. The opposite of hungrig.",example:"A: M\u00f6chtest du noch etwas?\nB: Nein danke, ich bin satt.\nA: Wirklich? Es gibt noch Kuchen.\nB: Na gut, ein kleines St\u00fcck vielleicht.",exampleSrc:"A: Would you like more?\nB: No thanks, I am full.\nA: Really? There is still cake.\nB: Well, a small piece maybe.",funFact:"Full, satisfied (after eating). 'Ich bin satt' means you have had enough. Germans say 'satt' not 'voll' for food fullness. 'Voll' means drunk."},
{type:"teach",trg:"genie\u00dfen",src:"to enjoy, to savor",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Irregular strong verb (genoss, genossen). 'Genie\u00dfe den Abend!'",example:"A: Genie\u00dft du den Abend?\nB: Ja, sehr! Das Essen ist toll.\nA: Und die Musik erst!\nB: Ich genie\u00dfe jeden Moment.",exampleSrc:"A: Are you enjoying the evening?\nB: Yes, very much! The food is great.\nA: And the music!\nB: I am savoring every moment.",funFact:"To enjoy, to savor. An irregular strong verb (genoss, genossen). From the same root as 'Genuss' (pleasure/enjoyment). A word for conscious, deliberate enjoyment."},
{type:"mc",q:"Der Biergarten ist warm und einladend. Welches Adjektiv beschreibt die Atmosph\u00e4re am besten?",opts:["gem\u00fctlich","richtig hungrig","sehr durstig","total satt"],ans:"gem\u00fctlich",hint:"Possibly the most untranslatable German word: cozy, comfortable, convivial."},
{type:"teach",trg:"spazieren gehen",src:"to go for a walk",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"A separable verb phrase. 'Wir gehen spazieren.' From Italian 'spaziare.'",example:"A: Wollen wir nach dem Essen spazieren gehen?\nB: Gute Idee! Durch den Park.\nA: Der Abend ist so sch\u00f6n.\nB: Ja, ein Spaziergang nach dem Essen ist gesund.",exampleSrc:"A: Shall we go for a walk after dinner?\nB: Good idea! Through the park.\nA: The evening is so beautiful.\nB: Yes, a walk after dinner is healthy.",funFact:"A separable verb phrase. From Italian 'spaziare' (to take space). The German evening walk (Spaziergang) is a cultural institution."},
{type:"teach",trg:"prost",src:"cheers",pos:"intj",gender:null,note:"From Latin 'prosit' (may it be beneficial). You MUST make eye contact when clinking glasses.",example:"A: Prost!\nB: Prost! Auf einen sch\u00f6nen Abend!\nA: Vergiss nicht: Augenkontakt!\nB: Stimmt, sonst gibt es sieben Jahre Pech.",exampleSrc:"A: Cheers!\nB: Cheers! To a lovely evening!\nA: Do not forget: eye contact!\nB: True, otherwise seven years of bad luck.",funFact:"From Latin 'prosit' (may it be beneficial). The universal German toast. You MUST make eye contact when clinking glasses. Not doing so supposedly brings seven years of bad luck."},
{type:"mc",q:"Mia kommt vom Lauftreff und sagt, sie ist sehr ___. Welches Wort beschreibt ihren Zustand?",opts:["satt","gem\u00fctlich","durstig","hungrig"],ans:"durstig",hint:"She wants something to drink first. This word comes from Durst."},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'Mahlzeit!', wenn ein Kollege es um die Mittagszeit sagt?",opts:["Es bedeutet auf Wiedersehen oder Tsch\u00fcss","Es ist eine formelle Entschuldigung","Es bedeutet immer Danke sch\u00f6n","Es ist ein Mittagsgru\u00df"],ans:"Es ist ein Mittagsgru\u00df",hint:"Mahl means meal, Zeit means time. Think about what happens at noon in German offices."},
{type:"fb",s:"Lukas, m\u00f6chtest du etwas trinken? -- Ja, ich bin sehr {1}!",a:["durstig"],opts:["durstig","hungrig","satt","gem\u00fctlich"],hint:"Lukas wants something to drink. Which adjective describes being thirsty?",sSrc:"Lukas, would you like something to drink? -- Yes, I am very thirsty!"},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'spazieren gehen'?",opts:["the terrace, the patio","to go for a walk","thirsty","the waitress"],ans:"to go for a walk",hint:"Italian loanword 'spaziare' (to stroll). A casual outing on foot, not athletic training."},
{type:"fb",s:"{1}!",a:["prost"],opts:["das Trinkgeld","satt","die Wirtin","prost"],hint:"The classic German toast when raising glasses. Latin origin: 'prosit' (may it be good).",sSrc:"Cheers!"},
{type:"mc",q:"Ich möchte den Abend in Ruhe ___.",opts:["genießen","spazieren","trinken","essen"],ans:"genießen",hint:"A verb meaning to savor, enjoy, or relish an experience fully."}
]},

// ─── Lesson 2: Brotzeit und Bratwurst ────────────────────────────────
{id:"deu_r18l2",title:"Brotzeit und Bratwurst",icon:"\uD83C\uDF54",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Brotzeit und Bratwurst",desc:"Time to fill the table. Learn kitchen equipment, ingredients, and food states. From Pfanne to Pflaume, from raw to cooked.",goals:["Name kitchen equipment and cooking vessels","Describe ingredients and their properties","Distinguish between raw and cooked food states"]},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Pfanne",src:"the pan, the skillet",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"From Latin 'patina.' 'Bratpfanne' (frying pan) is where Bratwurst gets its sizzle.",example:"A: Wo ist die Pfanne?\nB: Im Schrank, neben dem Herd.\nA: Ich brauche die gro\u00dfe Bratpfanne.\nB: Die mit dem schwarzen Griff?",exampleSrc:"A: Where is the pan?\nB: In the cabinet, next to the stove.\nA: I need the big frying pan.\nB: The one with the black handle?",funFact:"From Latin 'patina.' 'Bratpfanne' (frying pan) is where Bratwurst gets its sizzle. 'Etwas auf die Pfanne hauen' (to slap something on the pan) is slang for doing something boldly."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Kanne",src:"the jug, the pot, the pitcher",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"'Kaffeekanne' (coffee pot), 'Teekanne' (teapot), 'Gie\u00dfkanne' (watering can).",example:"A: Soll ich eine Kanne Kaffee machen?\nB: Ja, bitte! Eine gro\u00dfe Kanne.\nA: Mit Milch?\nB: Nein, schwarz.",exampleSrc:"A: Shall I make a pot of coffee?\nB: Yes, please! A big pot.\nA: With milk?\nB: No, black.",funFact:"A jug, pot, or pitcher. 'Kaffeekanne' (coffee pot), 'Teekanne' (teapot), 'Gie\u00dfkanne' (watering can). The -kanne compounds cover every kind of pouring vessel."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Sch\u00fcssel",src:"the bowl",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"From 'sch\u00fctten' (to pour). Not to be confused with 'Schl\u00fcssel' (key).",example:"A: Gib mir bitte die gro\u00dfe Sch\u00fcssel.\nB: F\u00fcr den Kartoffelsalat?\nA: Ja, wir brauchen viel Platz.\nB: Hier, die reicht bestimmt.",exampleSrc:"A: Please hand me the big bowl.\nB: For the potato salad?\nA: Yes, we need a lot of space.\nB: Here, this one should be enough.",funFact:"From 'sch\u00fctten' (to pour). A Sch\u00fcssel holds salads, soups, or Kartoffelsalat at the Biergarten. Not to be confused with 'Schl\u00fcssel' (key). One letter difference, completely different objects."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Dose",src:"the can, the tin",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"'Konservendose' (canned food). 'Dosenbier' (canned beer) is the budget option.",example:"A: Hast du eine Dose Tomaten?\nB: Ja, im Regal oben.\nA: Und Dosenbier?\nB: Im K\u00fchlschrank, ganz unten.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you have a can of tomatoes?\nB: Yes, on the top shelf.\nA: And canned beer?\nB: In the fridge, right at the bottom.",funFact:"A can or tin. 'Konservendose' (canned food). In many German regions, Dose also means a small container or box. 'Dosenbier' (canned beer) is the budget option at any German park gathering."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die T\u00fcte",src:"the bag (paper or plastic)",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"'Eine T\u00fcte Chips' (a bag of chips). In southern Germany: 'Sackerl' or 'Sack.'",example:"A: Brauchen Sie eine T\u00fcte?\nB: Nein danke, ich habe meinen Beutel.\nA: In Berlin sagt man T\u00fcte, in M\u00fcnchen Sackerl.\nB: Und in der Schweiz?",exampleSrc:"A: Do you need a bag?\nB: No thanks, I have my own bag.\nA: In Berlin they say T\u00fcte, in Munich Sackerl.\nB: And in Switzerland?",funFact:"A bag (paper or plastic). In northern Germany, T\u00fcte is universal. In southern Germany and Austria, they say 'Sackerl' or 'Sack.' Regional vocabulary at its finest."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"die Kanne",src:"the jug, the pot, the pitcher"},{trg:"die Sch\u00fcssel",src:"the bowl"},{trg:"die Dose",src:"the can, the tin"},{trg:"die T\u00fcte",src:"the bag (paper or plastic)"}]},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Zutat",src:"the ingredient",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"'Zu' (to/added) + 'Tat' (deed). Something 'added to the deed' of cooking.",example:"A: Welche Zutaten brauchen wir?\nB: Mehl, Eier und Zucker.\nA: Haben wir alles?\nB: Wir brauchen noch Butter.",exampleSrc:"A: Which ingredients do we need?\nB: Flour, eggs, and sugar.\nA: Do we have everything?\nB: We still need butter.",funFact:"'Zu' (to/added) + 'Tat' (deed/action). An ingredient, literally something 'added to the deed' of cooking. 'Zutaten' (plural) is what every recipe lists first."},
{type:"mc",q:"Chips kauft man in einer T\u00fcte. Tomaten kauft man in einer Dose. Was ist der Unterschied?",opts:["T\u00fcte ist aus Papier oder Plastik, Dose ist aus Metall","T\u00fcte und Dose sind dasselbe","T\u00fcte ist gr\u00f6\u00dfer","Dose ist aus Papier"],ans:"T\u00fcte ist aus Papier oder Plastik, Dose ist aus Metall",hint:"One is a bag, the other is a tin can. Different materials for different containers."},
{type:"fb",s:"Welche {1} brauchen wir f\u00fcr den Kuchen? -- Mehl, Eier und Zucker.",a:["Zutaten"],opts:["Zutaten","Pfannen","Kannen","Dosen"],hint:"Which plural noun means ingredients, from 'zu' (to) + 'Tat' (deed)?",sSrc:"Which ingredients do we need for the cake? -- Flour, eggs, and sugar."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Zwiebel",src:"the onion",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"From Latin 'cepulla' (small onion). In nearly every German dish.",example:"A: Kannst du die Zwiebeln schneiden?\nB: Ja, aber ich weine immer dabei.\nA: Versuch es mit einer Taucherbrille.\nB: Das ist nicht dein Ernst!",exampleSrc:"A: Can you cut the onions?\nB: Yes, but I always cry doing it.\nA: Try wearing swimming goggles.\nB: You are not serious!",funFact:"From Latin 'cepulla' (small onion). The Zwiebel is in nearly every German dish. 'Zwiebelkuchen' (onion tart) paired with Federwei\u00dfer (young wine) is an autumn tradition."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Pfeffer",src:"the pepper",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"From Latin 'piper,' which came from Sanskrit. Same root as English 'pepper.'",example:"A: Kannst du mir den Pfeffer geben?\nB: Hier, bitte. Schwarzer oder wei\u00dfer?\nA: Schwarzer Pfeffer, frisch gemahlen.\nB: Das macht alles besser.",exampleSrc:"A: Can you pass me the pepper?\nB: Here you go. Black or white?\nA: Black pepper, freshly ground.\nB: That makes everything better.",funFact:"From Latin 'piper,' which came from Sanskrit. 'Geh dahin, wo der Pfeffer w\u00e4chst!' (Go where the pepper grows!) means 'Get lost!' because pepper came from far away."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Mehl",src:"the flour",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"From Old High German 'melo' (ground grain). Related to English 'meal' and 'mill.'",example:"A: Wie viel Mehl brauchen wir?\nB: Zweihundert Gramm Mehl Typ 405.\nA: Was bedeutet 405?\nB: Das ist besonders feines Mehl zum Backen.",exampleSrc:"A: How much flour do we need?\nB: Two hundred grams of Type 405 flour.\nA: What does 405 mean?\nB: That is especially fine flour for baking.",funFact:"From Old High German 'melo' (ground grain). Related to English 'meal' (ground grain) and 'mill.' German baking depends on precise Mehl types: Type 405 (fine), 550, 1050 (coarse)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Fett",src:"the fat, the grease",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"Same root as English 'fat.' 'Fettarm' (low-fat), 'fettfrei' (fat-free).",example:"A: Gib etwas Fett in die Pfanne.\nB: Butter oder \u00d6l?\nA: \u00d6l ist ges\u00fcnder.\nB: Aber Butter schmeckt besser!",exampleSrc:"A: Put some fat in the pan.\nB: Butter or oil?\nA: Oil is healthier.\nB: But butter tastes better!",funFact:"Same root as English 'fat.' 'Ins Fettn\u00e4pfchen treten' (to step in the fat pot) means to make a social blunder."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Pilz",src:"the mushroom",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"From Latin 'pileus' (cap). Germans forage for Pilze in forests every autumn.",example:"A: Ich habe frische Pilze vom Markt.\nB: Steinpilze oder Champignons?\nA: Steinpilze! Zum Braten.\nB: Perfekt, mit Butter und Öl.",exampleSrc:"A: I have fresh mushrooms from the market.\nB: Porcini or champignons?\nA: Porcini! For frying.\nB: Perfect, with butter and oil.",funFact:"From Latin 'pileus' (cap). Germans forage for Pilze in forests every autumn. 'Pilzsammeln' (mushroom picking) is a beloved tradition but dangerous without expertise."},
{type:"fb",s:"Gib etwas {1} in die Pfanne. Butter oder \u00d6l.",a:["Fett"],opts:["Fett","Mehl","Pfeffer","Pilz"],hint:"Which neuter noun means fat or grease, the same root as English 'fat'?",sSrc:"Put some fat in the pan. Butter or oil."},
{type:"mc",q:"Der Pfeffer kommt aus fernen L\u00e4ndern. Was bedeutet 'Geh dahin, wo der Pfeffer w\u00e4chst'?",opts:["Geh einkaufen","Geh weg!","Geh kochen","Geh nach Indien"],ans:"Geh weg!",hint:"Since pepper grows far away, this idiom means 'Get lost!' or 'Go away!'"}
]},
{id:"deu_r18l2b",title:"Brotzeit und Bratwurst (Teil 2)",icon:"\uD83C\uDF54",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Brotzeit und Bratwurst (continued)",desc:"Continue practicing the vocabulary from this topic.",goals:["Review and practice key words"]},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Pflaume",src:"the plum",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"From Latin 'prunum.' 'Pflaumenkuchen' (plum cake) is a classic late-summer dessert.",example:"A: Die Pflaumen sind reif!\nB: Perfekt f\u00fcr Pflaumenkuchen.\nA: Hast du das Rezept von deiner Oma?\nB: Ja, mit Zimt und Streuseln.",exampleSrc:"A: The plums are ripe!\nB: Perfect for plum cake.\nA: Do you have your grandma's recipe?\nB: Yes, with cinnamon and crumble.",funFact:"From Latin 'prunum' via Germanic transformation. 'Pflaumenkuchen' (plum cake) is a classic late-summer dessert. In slang, 'Du Pflaume!' means 'You dolt!' but gently."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Aprikose",src:"the apricot",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"From Arabic 'al-barquq' through Latin. In Austria: 'Marille.'",example:"A: Magst du Aprikosen?\nB: Ja, sehr! Besonders als Marmelade.\nA: In \u00d6sterreich sagt man Marille.\nB: Gleiche Frucht, anderes Wort.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you like apricots?\nB: Yes, very much! Especially as jam.\nA: In Austria they say Marille.\nB: Same fruit, different word.",funFact:"From Arabic 'al-barquq' through Latin. In Austria, they say 'Marille' instead of Aprikose. Same fruit, different word depending on which side of the border you stand."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Frucht",src:"the fruit",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"From Latin 'fructus.' The formal word. Casual German uses 'Obst' for fresh fruit.",example:"A: Diese Frucht kenne ich nicht.\nB: Das ist eine Kaki. Probier mal!\nA: Mmm, s\u00fc\u00df und weich.\nB: Fr\u00fcchtetee damit schmeckt auch gut.",exampleSrc:"A: I do not know this fruit.\nB: That is a persimmon. Try it!\nA: Mmm, sweet and soft.\nB: Fruit tea with it also tastes good.",funFact:"From Latin 'fructus.' 'Fr\u00fcchtetee' (fruit tea) is what Germans drink when they do not want caffeine. Die Frucht is the formal word. Casual German uses 'Obst' for fresh fruit."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Geb\u00e4ck",src:"the pastries, the baked goods",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"From 'backen' (to bake). The Ge- prefix makes it collective: all baked goods.",example:"A: Das Geb\u00e4ck hier ist fantastisch.\nB: Ja, alles frisch vom B\u00e4cker.\nA: Ich nehme ein Croissant und ein Br\u00f6tchen.\nB: Gute Wahl!",exampleSrc:"A: The pastries here are fantastic.\nB: Yes, everything fresh from the baker.\nA: I will take a croissant and a bread roll.\nB: Good choice!",funFact:"From 'backen' (to bake). The Ge- prefix makes it collective: all baked goods together. Cookies, pastries, bread rolls. Das Geb\u00e4ck is neuter, like most Ge- collective nouns."},
{type:"teach",trg:"drin",src:"in it, inside (colloquial)",pos:"adv",gender:null,note:"Colloquial contraction of 'darin' (in it/there).\nVery common in spoken German.",example:"A: Was ist da drin?\nB: Kartoffelsalat und Würstchen.\nA: Ist Pfeffer auch drin?\nB: Ja, und Zwiebeln!",exampleSrc:"A: What is in there?\nB: Potato salad and sausages.\nA: Is pepper in it too?\nB: Yes, and onions!",funFact:"Drin is the casual version of darin, just as drauf is casual for darauf and drüber for darüber. In everyday speech, Germans almost always use the short forms."},
{type:"mc",q:"In welchem Gef\u00e4\u00df serviert man Kartoffelsalat?",opts:["in einer Pfanne","in einer Sch\u00fcssel","in einer Dose","in einer T\u00fcte"],ans:"in einer Sch\u00fcssel",hint:"A deep, round container for serving salads and soups."},
{type:"fb",s:"Schneid bitte die {1}! Aber Vorsicht, du wirst weinen.",a:["Zwiebeln"],opts:["Zwiebeln","Pflaumen","Aprikosen","Fr\u00fcchte"],hint:"Which vegetable from Latin 'cepulla' makes you cry when cutting?",sSrc:"Please cut the onions! But careful, you will cry."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Picknick",src:"the picnic",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"Borrowed from French 'pique-nique.' The Biergarten is a permanent communal Picknick.",example:"A: Wollen wir ein Picknick im Park machen?\nB: Gute Idee! Ich bringe den Salat.\nA: Und ich bringe Brot und K\u00e4se.\nB: Perfekt, um drei Uhr am See?",exampleSrc:"A: Shall we have a picnic in the park?\nB: Good idea! I will bring the salad.\nA: And I will bring bread and cheese.\nB: Perfect, at three o'clock by the lake?",funFact:"Borrowed from French 'pique-nique.' Germans love a Picknick in the park: blanket, bread, cheese, wine. The Biergarten is essentially a permanent communal Picknick."},
{type:"teach",trg:"roh",src:"raw, uncooked",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"'Rohes Fleisch' (raw meat), 'Rohkost' (raw vegetables/health food). Related to English 'raw.'",example:"A: Ist das Fleisch noch roh?\nB: Ja, es muss noch zehn Minuten auf den Grill.\nA: Rohes Fleisch ist gef\u00e4hrlich.\nB: Nicht in Deutschland: Mett ist roh und beliebt!",exampleSrc:"A: Is the meat still raw?\nB: Yes, it needs ten more minutes on the grill.\nA: Raw meat is dangerous.\nB: Not in Germany: Mett is raw and popular!",funFact:"'Rohes Fleisch' (raw meat), 'Rohkost' (raw vegetables/health food). Related to English 'raw' through Proto-Germanic. Germans eat some things raw that surprise foreigners: 'Mett' (raw minced pork) is a real thing."},
{type:"teach",trg:"gar",src:"cooked, done",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"'Das Fleisch ist gar' (The meat is done). Also an adverb: 'gar nicht' (not at all).",example:"A: Ist die Bratwurst schon gar?\nB: Noch nicht, noch zwei Minuten.\nA: Ich mag sie gar nicht roh.\nB: Keine Sorge, sie wird perfekt!",exampleSrc:"A: Is the bratwurst done yet?\nB: Not yet, two more minutes.\nA: I do not like it raw at all.\nB: Do not worry, it will be perfect!",funFact:"Cooked, done (as an adjective). 'Das Fleisch ist gar' (The meat is done). Also an adverb meaning 'at all' or 'even': 'gar nicht' (not at all). Two completely different meanings in one word."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"roh",src:"raw/uncooked"},{trg:"gar",src:"cooked/done"},{trg:"Zutat",src:"ingredient"},{trg:"Frucht",src:"fruit"}]},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Marille",src:"the apricot (Austrian)",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Austrian word for Aprikose. From Italian amarella.\nMarillenknödel = apricot dumplings, an Austrian classic.",example:"A: Was ist eine Marille?\nB: Das ist die österreichische Aprikose.\nA: Sind Marillen süß?\nB: Ja, sehr süß und fruchtig.",exampleSrc:"A: What is a Marille?\nB: That is the Austrian apricot.\nA: Are Marillen sweet?\nB: Yes, very sweet and fruity.",funFact:"Marille comes from Italian amarella (little bitter one). Marillenknödel are one of Austria's most beloved desserts. The Wachau region is famous for its Marillen orchards."},
{type:"mc",q:"In \u00d6sterreich hei\u00dft 'Aprikose' anders. Wie sagt man dort?",opts:["Frucht","Pflaume (nein)","Marille","Zwiebel"],ans:"Marille",hint:"This is the Austrian word for the same fruit. It comes from Italian 'amarella.'"},
{type:"fb",s:"Zum Fr\u00fchst\u00fcck esse ich gerne frisches {1} vom B\u00e4cker.",a:["Geb\u00e4ck"],opts:["Geb\u00e4ck","Picknick","Mehl","Fett"],hint:"The collective noun for all baked goods, with the Ge- prefix.",sSrc:"For breakfast I like to eat fresh pastries from the baker."},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'die Pflaume'?",opts:["the plum","the bowl","the fat, the grease","the can, the tin"],ans:"the plum",hint:"Sounds like its English equivalent. A purple stone fruit used in German cakes and jams."},
{type:"fb",s:"Was ist da {1}?",a:["drin"],opts:["die Frucht","die Sch\\u00fcssel","die Dose","drin"],hint:"Contraction of 'darin' (in there). A colloquial adverb for something being inside.",sSrc:"What is in there?"}
]},

// ─── Lesson 3: Die Spargel-Panik ────────────────────────────────────
{id:"deu_r18l3",title:"Die Spargel-Panik",icon:"\uD83E\uDD66",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Die Spargel-Panik",desc:"Heinrich calls in a panic: Spargelzeit ends June 24! Learn the difference between 'als' and 'wenn,' plus food shopping and nutrition vocabulary.",goals:["Understand the German obsession with Spargelzeit","Learn als (one-time past) vs wenn (repeated/conditional)","Pick up food shopping and nutrition vocabulary"]},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Saison",src:"the season (food/sports)",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"From French 'saison.' Spargelzeit is Germany's most famous food Saison.",example:"A: Wann ist Erdbeer-Saison?\nB: Von Mai bis Juli.\nA: Und Spargel-Saison?\nB: Mitte April bis zum vierundzwanzigsten Juni.",exampleSrc:"A: When is strawberry season?\nB: From May to July.\nA: And asparagus season?\nB: Mid-April to the twenty-fourth of June.",funFact:"From French 'saison.' Spargelzeit is Germany's most famous food Saison: mid-April to June 24. Germans eat 1.7 kg of Spargel per person per year."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Ernte",src:"the harvest",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"From 'ernten' (to harvest). 'Erntezeit' (harvest time) is peak season for farmers.",example:"A: Die Ernte war dieses Jahr gut.\nB: Ja, der Sommer war perfekt.\nA: Besonders die Spargelernte.\nB: Die beste seit Jahren!",exampleSrc:"A: The harvest was good this year.\nB: Yes, the summer was perfect.\nA: Especially the asparagus harvest.\nB: The best in years!",funFact:"Harvest. From 'ernten' (to harvest). 'Erntezeit' (harvest time) is when German farmers are busiest. The word carries weight in a country where seasonal eating is still important."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Quittung",src:"the receipt",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"From Latin 'quietare' (to settle). Germans keep Quittungen for everything.",example:"A: Kann ich die Quittung haben?\nB: Nat\u00fcrlich, hier bitte.\nA: Ich brauche sie f\u00fcr die Steuererkl\u00e4rung.\nB: Typisch deutsch!",exampleSrc:"A: Can I have the receipt?\nB: Of course, here you go.\nA: I need it for the tax return.\nB: Typically German!",funFact:"From Latin 'quietare' (to settle). 'Kann ich die Quittung haben?' is essential shopping vocabulary. Germans keep Quittungen for everything, especially for tax returns."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Rabatt",src:"the discount",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"From Italian 'rabatto.' A discount or reduction.",example:"A: Gibt es einen Rabatt auf den Spargel?\nB: Ja, zehn Prozent, weil die Saison fast vorbei ist.\nA: Dann nehme ich zwei Kilo!\nB: Kluge Entscheidung.",exampleSrc:"A: Is there a discount on the asparagus?\nB: Yes, ten percent, because the season is almost over.\nA: Then I will take two kilos!\nB: Smart decision.",funFact:"From Italian 'rabatto' (discount). 'Sonderangebot' (special offer) and 'Rabatt' are the words that make German shoppers happy."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Sonderangebot",src:"the special offer",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"'Sonder' (special) + 'Angebot' (offer). Neuter because Angebot is neuter.",example:"A: Schau mal, Spargel im Sonderangebot!\nB: Nur drei Euro das Kilo!\nA: Heinrich w\u00e4re begeistert.\nB: Ruf ihn an!",exampleSrc:"A: Look, asparagus on special offer!\nB: Only three euros per kilo!\nA: Heinrich would be thrilled.\nB: Call him!",funFact:"'Sonder' (special) + 'Angebot' (offer). German supermarkets advertise Sonderangebote in weekly flyers. Das Sonderangebot is neuter because Angebot is neuter. Compound gender rule."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"die Ernte",src:"the harvest"},{trg:"die Quittung",src:"the receipt"},{trg:"der Rabatt",src:"the discount"},{trg:"das Sonderangebot",src:"the special offer"}]},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Schlange",src:"the snake, the queue",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"'Schlange stehen' (to stand in line) makes the queue a snake.",example:"A: Oh nein, die Schlange ist so lang!\nB: Ja, alle wollen den letzten Spargel.\nA: Wir m\u00fcssen Schlange stehen.\nB: Das geh\u00f6rt zum deutschen Alltag.",exampleSrc:"A: Oh no, the queue is so long!\nB: Yes, everyone wants the last asparagus.\nA: We have to stand in line.\nB: That is part of German daily life.",funFact:"A snake AND a queue. 'Schlange stehen' (to stand in line) makes the queue a snake. Germans queue precisely but not always patiently."},
{type:"fb",s:"Gibt es einen {1} auf den Spargel? -- Ja, zehn Prozent!",a:["Rabatt"],opts:["Rabatt","Sonderangebot","Quittung","Saison"],hint:"Which masculine noun means a discount or price reduction, from Italian?",sSrc:"Is there a discount on the asparagus? -- Yes, ten percent!"},
{type:"mc",q:"Spargelzeit endet am 24. Juni. Was ist eine 'Saison'?",opts:["ein prozentualer Preisnachlass","eine besonders gute Ernte","eine gültige Quittung","eine zeitlich begrenzte Periode"],ans:"eine zeitlich begrenzte Periode",hint:"From French. A limited period for a specific food, sport, or activity."}
]},
{id:"deu_r18l3b",title:"Die Spargel-Panik (Teil 2)",icon:"\uD83E\uDD66",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Die Spargel-Panik (continued)",desc:"Continue practicing the vocabulary from this topic.",goals:["Review and practice key words"]},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Backofen",src:"the oven",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"'Back' (bake) + 'Ofen' (oven). Every German kitchen has one.",example:"A: Heize den Backofen auf 180 Grad vor.\nB: Ober- und Unterhitze?\nA: Ja, f\u00fcr den Spargelauflauf.\nB: In zwanzig Minuten ist er hei\u00df.",exampleSrc:"A: Preheat the oven to 180 degrees.\nB: Top and bottom heat?\nA: Yes, for the asparagus casserole.\nB: It will be hot in twenty minutes.",funFact:"'Back' (bake) + 'Ofen' (oven). 'Den Backofen auf 180 Grad vorheizen' (Preheat the oven to 180 degrees) begins every German recipe. Celsius, naturally."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Nahrungsmittel",src:"the foodstuff",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"'Nahrung' (nourishment) + 'Mittel' (means). The formal, official word for food.",example:"A: Nahrungsmittel m\u00fcssen korrekt beschriftet sein.\nB: Das steht im Gesetz.\nA: Jede Zutat muss auf der Verpackung stehen.\nB: Deutschland nimmt das ernst.",exampleSrc:"A: Foodstuffs must be labeled correctly.\nB: That is the law.\nA: Every ingredient must be on the packaging.\nB: Germany takes that seriously.",funFact:"'Nahrung' (nourishment) + 'Mittel' (means/agent). The formal, official word for food. You see it on packaging and in regulations. More technical than 'Essen' (food/eating)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Ern\u00e4hrung",src:"the nutrition, the diet",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"From 'ern\u00e4hren' (to nourish). Covers your entire relationship with food.",example:"A: Achtest du auf deine Ern\u00e4hrung?\nB: Ja, ich esse viel Obst und Gem\u00fcse.\nA: Gesunde Ern\u00e4hrung ist wichtig.\nB: Besonders im Sommer mit frischem Spargel!",exampleSrc:"A: Do you watch your diet?\nB: Yes, I eat lots of fruit and vegetables.\nA: Healthy nutrition is important.\nB: Especially in summer with fresh asparagus!",funFact:"From 'ern\u00e4hren' (to nourish). 'Gesunde Ern\u00e4hrung' (healthy nutrition) is a topic Germans take seriously. Die Ern\u00e4hrung covers your entire relationship with food."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Di\u00e4t",src:"the diet",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"From Greek 'diaita' (way of life). Can also mean a special medical diet.",example:"A: Machst du eine Di\u00e4t?\nB: Nein, ich esse einfach weniger Zucker.\nA: Das ist auch eine Art Di\u00e4t.\nB: Stimmt, aber es f\u00fchlt sich nicht so an.",exampleSrc:"A: Are you on a diet?\nB: No, I just eat less sugar.\nA: That is also a kind of diet.\nB: True, but it does not feel like it.",funFact:"From Greek 'diaita' (way of life). In German, Di\u00e4t can also mean a special medical diet, not just weight loss. Politicians' salaries are also called 'Di\u00e4ten.'"},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Vitamin",src:"the vitamin",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"Coined in 1912 from Latin 'vita' (life) + 'amine.' 'Vitamin C' is pronounced 'Vitamin Tsay.'",example:"A: Spargel hat viele Vitamine.\nB: Besonders Vitamin C und K.\nA: Deshalb ist er so gesund.\nB: Und lecker!",exampleSrc:"A: Asparagus has many vitamins.\nB: Especially vitamin C and K.\nA: That is why it is so healthy.\nB: And delicious!",funFact:"Coined in 1912 from Latin 'vita' (life) + 'amine.' Germans are vitamin-conscious. 'Vitamin C' is pronounced 'Vitamin Tsay.' The health-food market in Germany is enormous."},
{type:"mc",q:"Die Milch im K\u00fchlschrank ist noch bis Mittwoch ___. Was passt?",opts:["haltbar","reif","roh","vegetarisch"],ans:"haltbar",hint:"This adjective describes how long food keeps. From 'halten' (to hold) plus '-bar' (able)."},
{type:"fb",s:"'Mindestens {1} bis...' steht auf jeder deutschen Lebensmittelverpackung.",a:["haltbar"],opts:["haltbar","reif","roh","gar"],hint:"Best before... Which adjective means 'having a shelf life'?",sSrc:"'Best before...' is printed on every German food package."},
{type:"teach",trg:"reif",src:"ripe, mature",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"'Der Apfel ist reif.' Also figurative: 'reif f\u00fcr etwas sein' (to be ready for something).",example:"A: Sind die Erdbeeren schon reif?\nB: Ja, sie sind perfekt rot.\nA: Dann pfl\u00fccken wir sie heute.\nB: Die reifen sind die s\u00fc\u00dfesten.",exampleSrc:"A: Are the strawberries ripe yet?\nB: Yes, they are perfectly red.\nA: Then we will pick them today.\nB: The ripe ones are the sweetest.",funFact:"Ripe, mature. Also used figuratively: 'reif f\u00fcr etwas sein' (to be ready for something). 'Ich bin reif f\u00fcr den Urlaub' (I am ready for vacation)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"haltbar",src:"durable, having a shelf life",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"'Halt' (hold) + '-bar' (able). 'Mindestens haltbar bis...' (Best before...).",example:"A: Wie lange ist die Milch haltbar?\nB: Bis n\u00e4chsten Mittwoch.\nA: Und die Konserven?\nB: Die sind Jahre haltbar.",exampleSrc:"A: How long does the milk keep?\nB: Until next Wednesday.\nA: And the canned goods?\nB: They keep for years.",funFact:"'Halt' (hold) + '-bar' (able). 'Mindestens haltbar bis...' (Best before...) appears on every German food package. The -bar suffix works like English '-able.'"},
{type:"teach",trg:"vegetarisch",src:"vegetarian",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"From Latin 'vegetare' (to enliven). Germany has high rates of vegetarianism.",example:"A: Gibt es etwas Vegetarisches?\nB: Ja, Kartoffelsalat und Spargelsuppe.\nA: Perfekt, ich esse kein Fleisch.\nB: In Berlin ist das ganz normal.",exampleSrc:"A: Is there anything vegetarian?\nB: Yes, potato salad and asparagus soup.\nA: Perfect, I do not eat meat.\nB: In Berlin that is completely normal.",funFact:"From Latin 'vegetare' (to enliven). Germany has one of the highest rates of vegetarianism in Europe. Berlin alone has over 60 fully vegetarian restaurants."},
{type:"teach",trg:"zubereiten",src:"to prepare (food)",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"'Zu' (to) + 'bereiten' (to prepare). More specific than 'vorbereiten.' Separable.",example:"A: Wie bereitet man Spargel zu?\nB: Sch\u00e4len, kochen, mit Butter servieren.\nA: Wie lange kocht er?\nB: Zehn bis f\u00fcnfzehn Minuten.",exampleSrc:"A: How do you prepare asparagus?\nB: Peel, boil, serve with butter.\nA: How long does it cook?\nB: Ten to fifteen minutes.",funFact:"'Zu' (to) + 'bereiten' (to prepare). More specific than 'vorbereiten' (general preparation). Separable: 'Ich bereite das Essen zu.'"},
{type:"teach",trg:"mischen",src:"to mix",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Regular verb. 'Einen Salat mischen' (to toss a salad). Related to English 'mix.'",example:"A: Kannst du den Salat mischen?\nB: Klar, mit welchem Dressing?\nA: Essig und \u00d6l.\nB: Ich mische alles zusammen.",exampleSrc:"A: Can you toss the salad?\nB: Sure, with which dressing?\nA: Vinegar and oil.\nB: I will mix everything together.",funFact:"To mix. Regular verb. 'Einen Salat mischen' (to toss a salad), 'Karten mischen' (to shuffle cards). Related to English 'mix' through Latin 'miscere.'"},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"haltbar",src:"durable, having a shelf life"},{trg:"vegetarisch",src:"vegetarian"},{trg:"zubereiten",src:"to prepare (food)"},{trg:"mischen",src:"to mix"}]},
{type:"teach",trg:"sp\u00fclen",src:"to rinse, to wash (dishes)",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"'Geschirr sp\u00fclen' (to wash dishes). Also 'die Toilette sp\u00fclen' (to flush).",example:"A: Wer sp\u00fclt heute das Geschirr?\nB: Du! Ich habe gestern gesp\u00fclt.\nA: Wir brauchen eine Sp\u00fclmaschine.\nB: Stimmt, Handsp\u00fclen dauert ewig.",exampleSrc:"A: Who washes the dishes today?\nB: You! I washed them yesterday.\nA: We need a dishwasher.\nB: True, hand-washing takes forever.",funFact:"To rinse or wash (dishes). 'Geschirr sp\u00fclen' (to wash dishes). Also 'die Toilette sp\u00fclen' (to flush the toilet). The Sp\u00fclmaschine is the dishwasher."},
{type:"tip",title:"als vs wenn: Zwei W\u00f6rter f\u00fcr 'when'",text:"German has two words where English has one.\n\nALS = one specific moment in the past.\n'Als ich ein Kind war...' (When I was a child...)\n'Als Heinrich anrief...' (When Heinrich called...)\n\nWENN = every time, repeatedly, or hypothetically.\n'Wenn ich Spargel esse...' (When/whenever I eat asparagus...)\n'Wenn die Saison endet...' (When the season ends...)\n\nMemory trick:\nALS = ONCE in the past.\nWENN = WHENEVER or IF.\n\nHildi says 'Als ich ein Kind war' (one specific past). Lukas says 'Wenn man den letzten Spargel verpasst' (every year, repeated).",deepDive:"The distinction is strict in German. You cannot use 'wenn' for a single past event, and you cannot use 'als' for repeated or present events. In reported speech or written German, the rule holds firm. Some learners think 'als' means 'as' and 'wenn' means 'when/if,' but the real key is: was it a one-time past event (als) or is it repeated/habitual/conditional (wenn)?"},
{type:"verb_table",title:"als vs wenn (when)",note:"Als = one specific past event. Wenn = repeated, habitual, or hypothetical.",groups:[{label:"als (einmalig in der Vergangenheit)",rows:[{pronoun:"Als ich ankam,",form:"war alles bereit.",src:"When I arrived, everything was ready."},{pronoun:"Als wir Kinder waren,",form:"spielten wir im Garten.",src:"When we were children, we played in the garden."},{pronoun:"Als Heinrich anrief,",form:"sa\u00dfen wir im Biergarten.",src:"When Heinrich called, we were sitting in the beer garden."}]},{label:"wenn (wiederholt / hypothetisch)",rows:[{pronoun:"Wenn ich Hunger habe,",form:"esse ich Brot.",src:"When(ever) I am hungry, I eat bread."},{pronoun:"Wenn die Saison endet,",form:"gibt es keinen Spargel.",src:"When the season ends, there is no asparagus."},{pronoun:"Wenn ich k\u00f6nnte,",form:"w\u00fcrde ich jeden Tag grillen.",src:"If I could, I would grill every day."}]}]},
{type:"mc",q:"Erg\u00e4nze: '_____ ich gestern im Biergarten war, habe ich Spargel bestellt.'",opts:["Ob","Als","Wenn","Weil"],ans:"Als",hint:"Yesterday is a single, specific moment in the past. Which word means 'when' for one-time events?"},
{type:"fb",s:"{1} die Spargelzeit endet, sind die Deutschen immer traurig.",a:["Wenn"],opts:["Wenn","Als","Ob","Weil"],hint:"The asparagus season ends EVERY year. This is a repeated event.",sSrc:"When the asparagus season ends, Germans are always sad."},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'der Backofen'?",opts:["the special offer","the oven","vegetarian","to prepare (food)"],ans:"the oven",hint:"Backen (to bake) + Ofen (furnace/stove). The heated box in the kitchen for baking."},
{type:"fb",s:"Wie sagt man 'the foodstuff' auf Deutsch? {1}",a:["das Nahrungsmittel"],opts:["das Nahrungsmittel","haltbar","das Vitamin","reif"],hint:"Nahrung (nourishment) + Mittel (means/agent). A general term for edible products.",sSrc:"How do you say 'the foodstuff' in German?"},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'das Vitamin'?",opts:["the nutrition, the diet","the receipt","the discount","the vitamin"],ans:"the vitamin",hint:"Latin/scientific cognate. Identical meaning across all European languages. Essential nutrients."},
{type:"fb",s:"Wie sagt man 'to prepare (food)' auf Deutsch? {1}",a:["zubereiten"],opts:["die Schlange","die Ern\\u00e4hrung","vegetarisch","zubereiten"],hint:"Zu- (to/toward) + bereiten (to make ready). To get food ready for eating.",sSrc:"How do you say 'to prepare (food)' in German?"},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'mischen'?",opts:["to mix","the foodstuff","the discount","the nutrition, the diet"],ans:"to mix",hint:"Sounds like its English equivalent (same Germanic root). To combine ingredients together."},
{type:"fb",s:"Wer {1} heute ab? Die Teller stehen noch in der Küche.",a:"spült",opts:["spült","mischt","kocht","schneidet"],hint:"A verb meaning to wash dishes or rinse something with water.",sSrc:"Who does the dishes today? The plates are still in the kitchen."}
]},

// ─── Lesson 4: Worauf freust du dich? ───────────────────────────────
{id:"deu_r18l4",title:"Worauf freust du dich?",icon:"\uD83D\uDCA1",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Worauf freust du dich?",desc:"Some German verbs always come with a specific preposition. Learn the combos, then replace them with clever da- and wo- compounds.",goals:["Master verbs with fixed prepositions (sich freuen auf/\u00fcber, warten auf, denken an)","Learn da-compounds (darauf, dar\u00fcber) to replace prepositional phrases","Form questions with wo-compounds (worauf, wor\u00fcber)"]},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Konsum",src:"the consumption",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"From Latin 'consumere.' Covers everything from food to media consumption.",example:"A: Der Konsum von Spargel steigt jedes Jahr.\nB: Die Deutschen lieben Spargel.\nA: Der Konsum von Bio-Produkten w\u00e4chst auch.\nB: Ja, immer mehr Leute kaufen bio.",exampleSrc:"A: The consumption of asparagus increases every year.\nB: Germans love asparagus.\nA: The consumption of organic products is also growing.\nB: Yes, more and more people buy organic.",funFact:"From Latin 'consumere.' 'Konsumgesellschaft' (consumer society) is a word Germans use critically. Der Konsum is masculine."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Fl\u00fcssigkeit",src:"the liquid, the fluid",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"'Fl\u00fcssig' (liquid) + '-keit' (noun suffix). The -keit suffix always creates feminine nouns.",example:"A: Trinkst du genug Fl\u00fcssigkeit?\nB: Ich versuche es. Zwei Liter am Tag.\nA: Bei der Hitze brauchst du mehr.\nB: Stimmt, ich hole mir noch Wasser.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you drink enough fluids?\nB: I try. Two liters a day.\nA: In this heat you need more.\nB: True, I will get more water.",funFact:"'Fl\u00fcssig' (liquid) + '-keit' (noun suffix). 'Viel Fl\u00fcssigkeit trinken' (drink plenty of fluids) is standard German health advice. The -keit suffix always creates feminine nouns."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Alkohol",src:"the alcohol",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"From Arabic 'al-kuhl' (the kohl/essence). Germany has relaxed alcohol laws.",example:"A: Trinkst du Alkohol?\nB: Manchmal. Ein Bier im Biergarten.\nA: In Deutschland darf man ab sechzehn Bier trinken.\nB: Ja, aber Schnaps erst ab achtzehn.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you drink alcohol?\nB: Sometimes. A beer in the beer garden.\nA: In Germany you can drink beer from age sixteen.\nB: Yes, but spirits only from eighteen.",funFact:"From Arabic 'al-kuhl' (the kohl/essence). Germany has some of the most relaxed alcohol laws in Europe. Beer from age 16, spirits from 18."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Kakao",src:"the cocoa, the hot chocolate",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"From Nahuatl 'cacahuatl' via Spanish. 'Jemanden durch den Kakao ziehen' = to make fun of someone.",example:"A: M\u00f6chtest du Kakao oder Kaffee?\nB: Kakao, bitte. Mit Sahne.\nA: Du trinkst immer Kakao!\nB: Ja, das ist mein Lieblingsgetr\u00e4nk.",exampleSrc:"A: Would you like cocoa or coffee?\nB: Cocoa, please. With cream.\nA: You always drink cocoa!\nB: Yes, that is my favorite drink.",funFact:"From Nahuatl 'cacahuatl' via Spanish. 'Jemanden durch den Kakao ziehen' (to pull someone through the cocoa) means to make fun of someone."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Serviceangestellte",src:"the service employee (female)",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"'Service' + 'Angestellte' (employee). Gender-neutral alternative to Kellner/Kellnerin.",example:"A: Entschuldigung, k\u00f6nnen Sie uns helfen?\nB: Nat\u00fcrlich! Ich bin Ihre Serviceangestellte heute Abend.\nA: Wir h\u00e4tten gerne die Karte.\nB: Sofort!",exampleSrc:"A: Excuse me, can you help us?\nB: Of course! I am your service attendant this evening.\nA: We would like the menu.\nB: Right away!",funFact:"'Service' + 'Angestellte' (employee). The gender-neutral alternative to Kellner/Kellnerin. Modern German hospitality vocabulary."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"die Fl\u00fcssigkeit",src:"the liquid, the fluid"},{trg:"der Alkohol",src:"the alcohol"},{trg:"der Kakao",src:"the cocoa, the hot chocolate"},{trg:"die Serviceangestellte",src:"the service employee (female)"}]},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Vermietung",src:"the rental, the letting",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"From 'vermieten' (to rent out). Feminine because of -ung.",example:"A: Die Vermietung von Ferienwohnungen boomt.\nB: Besonders in Berlin.\nA: Siehst du das Schild? 'Vermietung ab Juni.'\nB: Vielleicht f\u00fcr den Sommer.",exampleSrc:"A: The rental of vacation apartments is booming.\nB: Especially in Berlin.\nA: Do you see the sign? 'Rental from June.'\nB: Maybe for the summer.",funFact:"From 'vermieten' (to rent out). 'Zimmervermietung' (room rental). Die Vermietung is feminine because of -ung. You see it on signs everywhere."},
{type:"fb",s:"Die {1} trinken in Deutschland viel. Zwei Liter am Tag ist gesund.",a:["Fl\u00fcssigkeit"],opts:["Fl\u00fcssigkeit","Alkohol","Di\u00e4t","Ern\u00e4hrung"],hint:"Which feminine noun describes any substance that flows, like water, juice, or oil?",sSrc:"Germans drink a lot of fluids. Two liters a day is healthy."},
{type:"mc",q:"Jemanden 'durch den Kakao ziehen' bedeutet...",opts:["jemanden einladen","jemanden auslachen","Kakao trinken","jemanden gr\u00fc\u00dfen"],ans:"jemanden auslachen",hint:"To pull someone through the cocoa: a German idiom meaning to mock or make fun of someone."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Vermittlung",src:"the mediation, the placement",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"From 'vermitteln' (to mediate/arrange). The -ung ending makes it feminine.",example:"A: Die Vermittlung hat mir eine Wohnung gefunden.\nB: Wie schnell?\nA: In nur zwei Wochen.\nB: Das ist in Berlin ein Wunder!",exampleSrc:"A: The agency found me an apartment.\nB: How quickly?\nA: In just two weeks.\nB: That is a miracle in Berlin!",funFact:"From 'vermitteln' (to mediate/arrange). 'Arbeitsvermittlung' (job placement), 'Zimmervermittlung' (accommodation service). The -ung ending makes it feminine."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Er\u00f6ffnung",src:"the opening, the inauguration",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"From 'er\u00f6ffnen' (to open formally). A formal event with speeches and ribbon-cutting.",example:"A: Kommst du zur Er\u00f6ffnung des neuen Biergartens?\nB: Ja, nat\u00fcrlich! Wann ist es?\nA: N\u00e4chsten Samstag um zw\u00f6lf.\nB: Ich bin dabei!",exampleSrc:"A: Are you coming to the opening of the new beer garden?\nB: Yes, of course! When is it?\nA: Next Saturday at noon.\nB: I will be there!",funFact:"From 'er\u00f6ffnen' (to open formally). 'Die Er\u00f6ffnung des Biergartens' (the opening of the beer garden). Grand openings in Germany involve speeches and ribbon-cutting."},
{type:"teach",trg:"bio",src:"organic",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Short for 'biologisch.' 'Bio-Bratwurst,' 'Bio-Bier.' Germany is Europe's largest organic market.",example:"A: Ist die Bratwurst bio?\nB: Ja, vom Bio-Bauernhof.\nA: Dann nehme ich zwei.\nB: Bio ist teurer, aber es lohnt sich.",exampleSrc:"A: Is the bratwurst organic?\nB: Yes, from an organic farm.\nA: Then I will take two.\nB: Organic is more expensive, but it is worth it.",funFact:"Short for 'biologisch.' Germany is the largest organic food market in Europe. The 'Bio' label is legally protected and strictly regulated."},
{type:"teach",trg:"biologisch",src:"biological, organic",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"From Greek 'bios' (life) + 'logos' (study). In food context it means organic.",example:"A: Ist das biologisch angebaut?\nB: Ja, ohne Pestizide.\nA: Biologische Landwirtschaft ist wichtig.\nB: F\u00fcr die Umwelt und f\u00fcr uns.",exampleSrc:"A: Is that organically grown?\nB: Yes, without pesticides.\nA: Organic farming is important.\nB: For the environment and for us.",funFact:"From Greek 'bios' (life) + 'logos' (study). 'Biologische Landwirtschaft' (organic farming). Longer form of 'bio,' used in formal or written contexts."},
{type:"teach",trg:"mager",src:"lean, thin, low-fat",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"'Magermilch' (skim milk), 'mageres Fleisch' (lean meat).",example:"A: Hast du Magermilch?\nB: Nein, nur Vollmilch.\nA: Ich achte auf meine Ern\u00e4hrung.\nB: Dann kaufe ich n\u00e4chstes Mal Magermilch.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you have skim milk?\nB: No, only whole milk.\nA: I watch my diet.\nB: Then I will buy skim milk next time.",funFact:"Lean, thin, low-fat. 'Magermilch' (skim milk), 'mageres Fleisch' (lean meat). Not a compliment when applied to food portions."},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'bio' auf einem Lebensmittel?",opts:["billig","biologisch angebaut","importiert","eingefroren"],ans:"biologisch angebaut",hint:"The EU-protected label for food grown without synthetic pesticides or chemicals. Look for the green leaf symbol."},
{type:"fb",s:"Die {1} hat uns freundlich bedient.",a:"Serviceangestellte",opts:["Serviceangestellte","Vermittlung","Wirtin","Kellnerin"],hint:"A feminine noun for a female service employee who assists customers.",sSrc:"The service employee served us in a friendly way."},
{type:"mc",q:"Die ___ hat einen Job für mich gefunden.",opts:["Vermittlung","Serviceangestellte","Ernährung","Eröffnung"],ans:"Vermittlung",hint:"A feminine noun for an agency that connects people, whether for jobs, housing, or mediation."}
]},
{id:"deu_r18l4b",title:"Worauf freust du dich? (Teil 2)",icon:"\uD83D\uDCA1",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Worauf freust du dich? (continued)",desc:"Continue practicing the vocabulary from this topic.",goals:["Review and practice key words"]},
{type:"fb",s:"Spargel hat viele {1}, besonders Vitamin C und K.",a:["Vitamine"],opts:["Vitamine","Di\u00e4ten","Ern\u00e4hrungen","Alkohol"],hint:"Which neuter plural noun names the essential nutrients in food, from a Latin root meaning life?",sSrc:"Asparagus has many vitamins, especially vitamin C and K."},
{type:"teach",trg:"spitz",src:"sharp, pointed",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"'Ein spitzer Stift' (a sharp pencil). Also 'spitze!' as slang for 'great!'",example:"A: Vorsicht, das Messer ist spitz!\nB: Danke, ich passe auf.\nA: Und wie war das Essen?\nB: Spitze!",exampleSrc:"A: Careful, the knife is sharp!\nB: Thanks, I will be careful.\nA: And how was the food?\nB: Great!",funFact:"Sharp, pointed. 'Ein spitzer Stift' (a sharp pencil). Also 'spitze!' as slang for 'great!' Related to English 'spit' (the pointed landform)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"er\u00f6ffnen",src:"to open (formally), to inaugurate",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"'Er-' (to begin/achieve) + '\u00f6ffnen' (to open). More formal than simply '\u00f6ffnen.'",example:"A: Wann er\u00f6ffnet der neue Biergarten?\nB: N\u00e4chste Woche.\nA: Wer er\u00f6ffnet ihn offiziell?\nB: Der B\u00fcrgermeister!",exampleSrc:"A: When does the new beer garden open?\nB: Next week.\nA: Who officially opens it?\nB: The mayor!",funFact:"'Er-' (to begin/achieve) + '\u00f6ffnen' (to open). You 'er\u00f6ffnen' a business, a meeting, or a Biergarten season. More formal than simply '\u00f6ffnen' (to open a door)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"konsumieren",src:"to consume",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"From Latin 'consumere.' More formal than 'essen' or 'trinken.'",example:"A: Deutsche konsumieren viel Bier.\nB: Aber weniger als fr\u00fcher.\nA: Der Konsum sinkt seit Jahren.\nB: Daf\u00fcr steigt der Weinkonsum.",exampleSrc:"A: Germans consume a lot of beer.\nB: But less than before.\nA: Consumption has been dropping for years.\nB: But wine consumption is increasing.",funFact:"From Latin 'consumere.' More formal than 'essen' or 'trinken.' 'Alkohol konsumieren' sounds more official. Used in health contexts and regulations."},
{type:"teach",trg:"l\u00f6sen",src:"to solve, to dissolve, to buy (a ticket)",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Three meanings in one verb. 'Ein Problem l\u00f6sen,' 'eine Fahrkarte l\u00f6sen.'",example:"A: Ich muss noch eine Fahrkarte l\u00f6sen.\nB: Am Automaten oder online?\nA: Online ist einfacher.\nB: Problem gel\u00f6st!",exampleSrc:"A: I still need to buy a ticket.\nB: At the machine or online?\nA: Online is easier.\nB: Problem solved!",funFact:"To solve, to dissolve, to buy (a ticket). 'Ein Problem l\u00f6sen,' 'Salz l\u00f6st sich in Wasser,' 'eine Fahrkarte l\u00f6sen.' Three meanings, one verb."},
{type:"teach",trg:"heben",src:"to lift, to raise",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Strong verb: heben, hob, gehoben. 'Ein Glas heben' (to raise a glass). Related to English 'heave.'",example:"A: Heben wir die Gl\u00e4ser!\nB: Prost! Auf den Sommer!\nA: Dieses Bierglas ist schwer.\nB: Ein Liter! Das ist Training.",exampleSrc:"A: Let us raise our glasses!\nB: Cheers! To summer!\nA: This beer glass is heavy.\nB: One liter! That is exercise.",funFact:"Strong verb: heben, hob, gehoben. 'Ein Glas heben' (to raise a glass) is what you do at 'Prost!' Related to English 'heave.'"},
{type:"tip",title:"Verben mit festen Pr\u00e4positionen",text:"Some German verbs always pair with a specific preposition. The preposition changes the meaning.\n\nsich freuen AUF = look forward to (future)\nsich freuen \u00dcBER = be happy about (present/past)\nwarten AUF = wait for\ndenken AN = think of\nbestehen AUF = insist on\nsich interessieren F\u00dcR = be interested in\n\nYou cannot swap the prepositions. Each combo is one fixed unit. Memorize them as pairs.\n\nExample from the story:\nHeinrich besteht AUF Spargel. (Heinrich insists ON asparagus.)\nVerumius freut sich AUF den Abend. (Verumius looks forward TO the evening.)",deepDive:"The case after the preposition matters too. 'Auf' with fixed-preposition verbs usually takes accusative: 'Ich warte auf DEN Kellner.' 'An' takes accusative with 'denken': 'Ich denke an DEN Abend.' These differ from the spatial use of the same prepositions, where the two-way prepositions take dative for location and accusative for direction."},
{type:"verb_table",title:"Verben mit festen Pr\u00e4positionen",note:"Each verb-preposition pair is a fixed unit. The preposition determines the case.",groups:[{label:"auf (Akkusativ)",rows:[{pronoun:"sich freuen auf",form:"Ich freue mich auf den Sommer.",src:"I look forward to summer."},{pronoun:"warten auf",form:"Wir warten auf den Kellner.",src:"We wait for the waiter."},{pronoun:"bestehen auf",form:"Heinrich besteht auf Spargel.",src:"Heinrich insists on asparagus."}]},{label:"\u00fcber (Akkusativ)",rows:[{pronoun:"sich freuen \u00fcber",form:"Sie freut sich \u00fcber das Geschenk.",src:"She is happy about the gift."},{pronoun:"sprechen \u00fcber",form:"Wir sprechen \u00fcber das Essen.",src:"We talk about the food."}]},{label:"an (Akkusativ)",rows:[{pronoun:"denken an",form:"Ich denke an den Abend.",src:"I think of the evening."},{pronoun:"sich erinnern an",form:"Er erinnert sich an den Biergarten.",src:"He remembers the beer garden."}]},{label:"f\u00fcr (Akkusativ)",rows:[{pronoun:"sich interessieren f\u00fcr",form:"Sie interessiert sich f\u00fcr Bio-Essen.",src:"She is interested in organic food."}]}]},
{type:"tip",title:"da- und wo-Komposita",text:"When you want to say 'about it' or 'for it,' German combines da- with a preposition:\n- darauf (on it), darüber (about it), daran (of it), dafür (for it)\n\nFor questions, combine wo- with a preposition:\n- worauf (on what), worüber (about what), woran (of what), wofür (for what)\n\nWhen the preposition starts with a vowel, an -r- is inserted for smoother pronunciation:\n- da- plus auf becomes darauf\n- wo- plus über becomes worüber\n\nExample:\n'Worauf wartest du?' -- 'Darauf, dass der Kellner kommt.'\n(What are you waiting for? -- For the waiter to come.)",deepDive:"Da-compounds replace prepositional phrases that refer to things (not people). For people, use the preposition plus a pronoun: 'Ich denke an ihn' (I think of him), NOT 'Ich denke daran' when referring to a person. Wo-compounds work the same way: 'An wen denkst du?' (Who are you thinking of?) for people, 'Woran denkst du?' (What are you thinking of?) for things."},
{type:"mc",q:"Verumius _____ sich _____ den Spargel. (freut sich auf etwas)",opts:["freut...\u00fcber","wartet...auf","freut...auf","denkt...an"],ans:"freut...auf",hint:"Looking forward to something in the FUTURE uses 'sich freuen' plus the preposition for future anticipation."},
{type:"mc",q:"Heinrich besteht auf Spargel. Er besteht _____ .",opts:["dar\u00fcber","daf\u00fcr","daran","darauf"],ans:"darauf",hint:"The verb is 'bestehen AUF.' Replace 'auf Spargel' with da + auf."},
{type:"fb",s:"{1} freust du dich? -- Auf den Sommer!",a:["Worauf"],opts:["Worauf","Wor\u00fcber","Woran","Wof\u00fcr"],hint:"The answer uses 'auf.' The question word combines 'wo' with 'auf.'",sSrc:"What are you looking forward to? -- To summer!"},
{type:"mc",q:"'_____ ich das erste Mal Spargel a\u00df, war ich \u00fcberrascht.' Welches Wort passt?",opts:["Als","Weil","Damit","Wenn"],ans:"Als",hint:"The FIRST time is a single, one-time past event. Which word is for that?"},
{type:"drag_fill",s:"Mia {1} sich {2} Bio-Essen. Sie denkt oft {3}.",blanks:{"1":"interessiert","2":"f\u00fcr","3":"daran"},pool:["interessiert","f\u00fcr","daran","freut","auf","darauf"],hint:"First: the verb for being interested plus its fixed preposition. Second: 'denken an' replaced with a da-compound.",sSrc:"Mia is interested in organic food. She often thinks about it."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"darauf",src:"on it / for it"},{trg:"dar\u00fcber",src:"about it"},{trg:"daran",src:"of it / to it"},{trg:"daf\u00fcr",src:"for it (purpose)"}]},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'spitz'?",opts:["sharp, pointed","biological, organic","the rental, the letting","the liquid, the fluid"],ans:"sharp, pointed",hint:"Describes a narrow, tapering end. Think of a pencil tip or a church steeple."},
{type:"fb",s:"Deutsche {1} viel Bier.",a:["konsumieren"],opts:["mager","die Vermietung","der Konsum","konsumieren"],hint:"Latin cognate of English 'consume'. A formal verb for using up food, drink, or goods.",sSrc:"Germans consume a lot of beer."},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'heben'?",opts:["the opening, the inauguration","to lift, to raise","sharp, pointed","the consumption"],ans:"to lift, to raise",hint:"A strong verb for moving something upward by force. 'Gewicht_____' = the sport of hoisting heavy things."},
{type:"fb",s:"Kannst du das Problem {1}?",a:"lösen",opts:["lösen","heben","konsumieren","mischen"],hint:"A verb meaning to solve, dissolve, or resolve a difficulty.",sSrc:"Can you solve the problem?"}
]},

// ─── Lesson 5: Lukas spielt ─────────────────────────────────────────
{id:"deu_r18l5",title:"Lukas spielt",icon:"\uD83C\uDFB8",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Lukas spielt",desc:"The golden hour fades to blue. Fairy lights glow. Lukas picks up his guitar. His band broke up last month. Tonight, he plays alone.",goals:["Practice als vs wenn in emotional contexts","Use verbs with fixed prepositions to describe feelings","Learn nature and agriculture vocabulary"]},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Wiese",src:"the meadow",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"'Liegewiese' (sunbathing lawn) is where Germans spread blankets in parks.",example:"A: Lass uns auf die Wiese setzen.\nB: Ja, das Gras ist weich.\nA: Die Wiese ist voller Blumen.\nB: Ein perfekter Sommerabend.",exampleSrc:"A: Let us sit on the meadow.\nB: Yes, the grass is soft.\nA: The meadow is full of flowers.\nB: A perfect summer evening.",funFact:"A meadow. 'Liegewiese' (sunbathing lawn) is where Germans spread their blankets in parks. 'Auf der gr\u00fcnen Wiese' is also business jargon for building from scratch."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Gras",src:"the grass",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"Same word and same root as English. 'Das Gras wachsen h\u00f6ren' = to be overly perceptive.",example:"A: Das Gras im Park ist so gr\u00fcn.\nB: Ja, es hat viel geregnet.\nA: Perfekt zum Picknicken.\nB: Aber nicht zu nass?",exampleSrc:"A: The grass in the park is so green.\nB: Yes, it rained a lot.\nA: Perfect for a picnic.\nB: But not too wet?",funFact:"Same word and same root as English. 'Das Gras wachsen h\u00f6ren' (to hear the grass grow) means to be overly sensitive or perceptive."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Feld",src:"the field",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"Cognate with English 'field.' Germany's agricultural Felder feed much of Europe.",example:"A: Schau dir die Felder an!\nB: Getreide, so weit man sehen kann.\nA: Die Ernte wird gut dieses Jahr.\nB: Ja, der Regen war perfekt.",exampleSrc:"A: Look at the fields!\nB: Grain, as far as you can see.\nA: The harvest will be good this year.\nB: Yes, the rain was perfect.",funFact:"Cognate with English 'field.' 'Feldforschung' (field research), 'Spielfeld' (playing field). Germany's agricultural Felder feed much of Europe."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Tuch",src:"the cloth, the scarf",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"'Halstuch' (neck scarf), 'Handtuch' (towel), 'Tischtuch' (tablecloth).",example:"A: Hast du ein Tuch dabei?\nB: Ja, mein Halstuch. Warum?\nA: Es wird k\u00fchler am Abend.\nB: Stimmt, nimm es.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you have a scarf with you?\nB: Yes, my neck scarf. Why?\nA: It is getting cooler in the evening.\nB: True, take it.",funFact:"A cloth or scarf. German compounds with Tuch name every type of fabric you drape: 'Halstuch' (neck scarf), 'Handtuch' (hand-cloth = towel), 'Tischtuch' (tablecloth)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Sack",src:"the sack, the bag",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Same word as English. In Austria: 'Sackerl' replaces 'T\u00fcte' for a small bag.",example:"A: Bring bitte einen Sack Kartoffeln mit.\nB: Vom Markt oder vom Supermarkt?\nA: Vom Markt, die sind frischer.\nB: Gut, ich nehme einen gro\u00dfen Sack.",exampleSrc:"A: Please bring a sack of potatoes.\nB: From the market or the supermarket?\nA: From the market, they are fresher.\nB: Good, I will take a big sack.",funFact:"Same word as English. In Austria and southern Germany, 'Sackerl' replaces 'T\u00fcte' for a small bag. 'Die Katze aus dem Sack lassen' (let the cat out of the bag) works in German too."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"das Gras",src:"the grass"},{trg:"das Feld",src:"the field"},{trg:"das Tuch",src:"the cloth, the scarf"},{trg:"der Sack",src:"the sack, the bag"}]},
{type:"teach",trg:"die B\u00fcchse",src:"the can, the tin, the box",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"'Konservenb\u00fcchse' (tin can). In some regions, B\u00fcchse and Dose are interchangeable.",example:"A: \u00d6ffne mal die B\u00fcchse mit den Bohnen.\nB: Wo ist der Dosenöffner?\nA: In der Schublade.\nB: Gefunden!",exampleSrc:"A: Open the can of beans.\nB: Where is the can opener?\nA: In the drawer.\nB: Found it!",funFact:"A can, tin, or box. 'Konservenb\u00fcchse' (tin can). In some regions, B\u00fcchse and Dose are interchangeable. Also historically a rifle or musket, from the cylindrical shape."},
{type:"fb",s:"Verumius sitzt auf der {1}. Das Gras ist weich und die Blumen bl\u00fchen.",a:["Wiese"],opts:["Wiese","Feld","Sack","B\u00fcchse"],hint:"Which feminine noun means meadow, where flowers grow and people spread blankets?",sSrc:"Verumius sits on the meadow. The grass is soft and the flowers bloom."},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet der Ausdruck 'Die Katze aus dem Sack lassen'?",opts:["eine Katze f\u00fcttern","einen Sack kaufen","ein Geheimnis verraten","eine Katze waschen"],ans:"ein Geheimnis verraten",hint:"To let the cat out of the bag: revealing something hidden. Same idiom in German and English."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Klo\u00df",src:"the dumpling",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Plural: Kl\u00f6\u00dfe. In southern Germany: Kn\u00f6del. Classic side dish.",example:"A: Magst du Kl\u00f6\u00dfe?\nB: Ja! Kartoffelkl\u00f6\u00dfe sind mein Lieblingsbeilage.\nA: In Bayern sagt man Kn\u00f6del.\nB: Gleich lecker, egal wie man es nennt.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you like dumplings?\nB: Yes! Potato dumplings are my favorite side.\nA: In Bavaria they say Kn\u00f6del.\nB: Equally delicious, no matter what you call them.",funFact:"A dumpling. Plural: Kl\u00f6\u00dfe. In southern Germany: Kn\u00f6del. 'Einen Klo\u00df im Hals haben' (to have a dumpling in your throat) means to be choked up with emotion."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Koch",src:"the cook, the chef",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"From Latin 'coquus.' 'Viele K\u00f6che verderben den Brei' (Too many cooks spoil the porridge).",example:"A: Der Koch hier ist fantastisch.\nB: Ja, alles schmeckt perfekt.\nA: Er kocht seit zwanzig Jahren.\nB: Erfahrung macht den Koch.",exampleSrc:"A: The chef here is fantastic.\nB: Yes, everything tastes perfect.\nA: He has been cooking for twenty years.\nB: Experience makes the chef.",funFact:"From Latin 'coquus.' 'Viele K\u00f6che verderben den Brei' (Too many cooks spoil the porridge). Same proverb, same meaning, same ancient wisdom."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die K\u00f6chin",src:"the cook, the chef (female)",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Koch + -in. More women lead professional kitchens in Germany now.",example:"A: Die K\u00f6chin hat ein neues Rezept.\nB: Was gibt es heute?\nA: Spargelsuppe mit Br\u00f6tchen.\nB: Klingt wunderbar!",exampleSrc:"A: The chef has a new recipe.\nB: What is there today?\nA: Asparagus soup with bread rolls.\nB: Sounds wonderful!",funFact:"Female cook. Koch + -in. More and more women lead professional kitchens in Germany, though the industry still has a long way to go."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Landwirtschaft",src:"the agriculture",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"'Land' (country/land) + 'Wirtschaft' (economy). Feminine because of -schaft.",example:"A: Die Landwirtschaft in Brandenburg ist wichtig.\nB: Ja, viele Bauernhöfe dort.\nA: Spargel kommt oft aus Brandenburg.\nB: Das beste Spargelgebiet Deutschlands!",exampleSrc:"A: Agriculture in Brandenburg is important.\nB: Yes, many farms there.\nA: Asparagus often comes from Brandenburg.\nB: The best asparagus region in Germany!",funFact:"'Land' (country/land) + 'Wirtschaft' (economy/management). Germany's agricultural sector feeds 80 million people efficiently."},
{type:"teach",trg:"aufwachen",src:"to wake up",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"'Auf' (up) + 'wachen' (to be awake). Separable: 'Ich wache um sechs auf.'",example:"A: Wann bist du aufgewacht?\nB: Um sechs Uhr. Die V\u00f6gel haben mich geweckt.\nA: Im Sommer wache ich auch fr\u00fch auf.\nB: Das Licht kommt so fr\u00fch!",exampleSrc:"A: When did you wake up?\nB: At six o'clock. The birds woke me.\nA: In summer I also wake up early.\nB: The light comes so early!",funFact:"'Auf' (up) + 'wachen' (to be awake). Not to be confused with 'aufwecken' (to wake someone else up). Aufwachen is what you do. Aufwecken is what your alarm does to you."},
{type:"mc",q:"Der Koch macht Kl\u00f6\u00dfe. In Bayern sagt man dazu...",opts:["Schwammerl","Kn\u00f6del","Sack","B\u00fcchse"],ans:"Kn\u00f6del",hint:"The Bavarian word for dumplings, a classic side dish."}
]},
{id:"deu_r18l5b",title:"Lukas spielt (Teil 2)",icon:"\uD83C\uDFB8",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Lukas spielt (continued)",desc:"Continue practicing the vocabulary from this topic.",goals:["Review and practice key words"]},
{type:"fb",s:"Die {1} ist wichtig f\u00fcr das Spargelgebiet Brandenburg. Viele Bauern arbeiten dort.",a:["Landwirtschaft"],opts:["Landwirtschaft","Wiese","Ernte","K\u00f6chin"],hint:"Land + Wirtschaft: which feminine noun means agriculture?",sSrc:"Agriculture is important for the asparagus region Brandenburg. Many farmers work there."},
{type:"teach",trg:"bl\u00fchen",src:"to bloom, to blossom",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"From the same root as 'Blume' (flower) and 'Bl\u00fcte' (blossom).",example:"A: Die Rosen bl\u00fchen wundersch\u00f6n.\nB: Ja, der Garten sieht toll aus.\nA: Im Fr\u00fchling bl\u00fcht alles.\nB: Meine Lieblingszeit!",exampleSrc:"A: The roses are blooming beautifully.\nB: Yes, the garden looks great.\nA: In spring everything blooms.\nB: My favorite time!",funFact:"To bloom, to blossom. Also figurative: 'Das Gesch\u00e4ft bl\u00fcht' (Business is blooming). From the same root as 'Blume' (flower) and 'Bl\u00fcte' (blossom)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"n\u00e4hern",src:"to approach, to come closer",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Often reflexive: 'sich n\u00e4hern.' From 'nah' (near).",example:"A: Wir n\u00e4hern uns dem Biergarten.\nB: Ich rieche schon die Bratwurst!\nA: Noch f\u00fcnf Minuten.\nB: Ich kann es kaum erwarten.",exampleSrc:"A: We are approaching the beer garden.\nB: I can already smell the bratwurst!\nA: Five more minutes.\nB: I can hardly wait.",funFact:"To approach, to come closer. Often reflexive: 'sich n\u00e4hern.' 'Wir n\u00e4hern uns dem Ziel' (We are approaching the goal). From 'nah' (near)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"pflanzen",src:"to plant",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"From Latin 'planta.' 'Einen Baum pflanzen.' Also a noun: die Pflanze (the plant).",example:"A: Hast du die Tomaten gepflanzt?\nB: Ja, gestern Nachmittag.\nA: Wann k\u00f6nnen wir ernten?\nB: In ungef\u00e4hr zwei Monaten.",exampleSrc:"A: Did you plant the tomatoes?\nB: Yes, yesterday afternoon.\nA: When can we harvest?\nB: In about two months.",funFact:"From Latin 'planta.' Germans take gardening seriously: Kleing\u00e4rten (allotment gardens) are a national institution."},
{type:"teach",trg:"wachsen",src:"to grow",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Strong verb: wachsen, wuchs, gewachsen. Not to be confused with 'wachsen' (to wax).",example:"A: Der Spargel w\u00e4chst unter der Erde.\nB: Deshalb ist er wei\u00df?\nA: Genau! Ohne Licht bleibt er wei\u00df.\nB: Faszinierend!",exampleSrc:"A: Asparagus grows under the ground.\nB: That is why it is white?\nA: Exactly! Without light it stays white.\nB: Fascinating!",funFact:"Strong verb: wachsen, wuchs, gewachsen. 'Kinder wachsen schnell.' Not to be confused with 'wachsen' (to wax), which is a different verb with different origins."},
{type:"teach",trg:"gie\u00dfen",src:"to pour, to water (plants)",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Strong verb: goss, gegossen. 'Blumen gie\u00dfen,' 'Es gie\u00dft' (It is pouring rain).",example:"A: Kannst du die Blumen gie\u00dfen?\nB: Klar, die sehen trocken aus.\nA: Jeden Abend gie\u00dfen im Sommer.\nB: Sonst gehen sie ein.",exampleSrc:"A: Can you water the flowers?\nB: Sure, they look dry.\nA: Water them every evening in summer.\nB: Otherwise they will die.",funFact:"To pour or to water (plants). 'Blumen gie\u00dfen' (to water flowers). Strong verb: goss, gegossen. 'Es gie\u00dft' means 'It is pouring rain.'"},
{type:"mc",q:"Lukas sagt: '_____ ich das letzte Konzert mit meiner Band spielte, wusste ich nicht, dass es das letzte war.'",opts:["Wenn","Obwohl","Als","Weil"],ans:"Als",hint:"The last concert was a single, specific moment in the past."},
{type:"fb",s:"Mia sagt: Lukas spricht nicht {1} seine Band.",a:["\u00fcber"],opts:["\u00fcber","auf","an","f\u00fcr"],hint:"The verb 'sprechen' pairs with which preposition to mean 'talk about'?",sSrc:"Mia says: Lukas does not talk about his band."},
{type:"mc",q:"Lukas denkt oft an seine Band. Er denkt oft _____ .",opts:["daf\u00fcr","darauf","dar\u00fcber","daran"],ans:"daran",hint:"'Denken AN' requires da + an. What is da + an?"},
{type:"drag_fill",s:"{1} Lukas seine Band hatte, spielten sie jeden Freitag. {2} er jetzt allein spielt, klingt es anders.",blanks:{"1":"Als","2":"Wenn"},pool:["Als","Wenn","Weil","Dass","Ob"],hint:"First blank: having the band was a specific period in the past. Second blank: playing alone is a repeated present situation.",sSrc:"When Lukas had his band, they played every Friday. When he plays alone now, it sounds different."},
{type:"mc",q:"Wie fragt man 'Woran denkt Lukas?' auf Englisch?",opts:["What is Lukas thinking about?","What is Lukas interested in?","What is Lukas waiting for?","What is Lukas happy about?"],ans:"What is Lukas thinking about?",hint:"The verb is 'denken AN.' The wo-compound combines wo + an."},
{type:"fb",s:"Die Blumen auf der {1} bl\u00fchen im Sommer.",a:["Wiese"],opts:["Wiese","Feld","Gras","Landwirtschaft"],hint:"The word for a meadow where flowers and grass grow.",sSrc:"The flowers on the meadow bloom in summer."},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'pflanzen'?",opts:["to pour, to water (plants)","to plant","to wake up","to grow"],ans:"to plant",hint:"Sounds like its English equivalent. To put seeds or seedlings into the soil to grow."},
{type:"fb",s:"Wie sagt man 'to grow' auf Deutsch? {1}",a:["wachsen"],opts:["wachsen","die B\\u00fcchse","das Tuch","gie\\u00dfen"],hint:"English cognate: 'wax' (as in 'waxing moon'). To increase in size naturally.",sSrc:"How do you say 'to grow' in German?"}
]},

// ─── Lesson 6: Dialekt auf dem Teller ───────────────────────────────
{id:"deu_r18l6",title:"Dialekt auf dem Teller",icon:"\uD83C\uDDE6\uD83C\uDDF9",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Dialekt auf dem Teller",desc:"German is not one language but many regional flavors. Learn farming vocabulary, then discover what Austrians and Swiss call their food.",goals:["Learn words for farming, residents, and pets","Discover Austrian and Swiss German food vocabulary","Understand regional identity through food words"]},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Bauer",src:"the farmer",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"From Old High German 'giburo' (neighbor). Also the pawn in chess.",example:"A: Der Bauer verkauft frischen Spargel.\nB: Direkt vom Feld!\nA: Bauernm\u00e4rkte sind in Berlin beliebt.\nB: Jeden Samstag am Maybachufer.",exampleSrc:"A: The farmer sells fresh asparagus.\nB: Straight from the field!\nA: Farmers' markets are popular in Berlin.\nB: Every Saturday at Maybachufer.",funFact:"From Old High German 'giburo' (neighbor, fellow dweller). Also the pawn in chess. 'Bauernregel' (farmer's rule) = weather proverbs based on centuries of agricultural observation."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Bauernhof",src:"the farm",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"'Bauer' + 'Hof' (yard/farm). Masculine because Hof is masculine.",example:"A: Warst du schon mal auf einem Bauernhof?\nB: Ja, als Kind. Wir haben Urlaub dort gemacht.\nA: Urlaub auf dem Bauernhof ist toll f\u00fcr Kinder.\nB: Und f\u00fcr Erwachsene!",exampleSrc:"A: Have you ever been to a farm?\nB: Yes, as a child. We vacationed there.\nA: Farm vacations are great for children.\nB: And for adults!",funFact:"'Bauer' + 'Hof' (yard/farm). 'Urlaub auf dem Bauernhof' (vacation on a farm) is a popular German family holiday."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Bewohner",src:"the resident, the inhabitant",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"From 'bewohnen' (to inhabit). The Be- prefix + wohnen = who lives somewhere.",example:"A: Wie viele Bewohner hat das Haus?\nB: Zw\u00f6lf Parteien.\nA: Kennen sich alle?\nB: Die meisten, ja. Wir grillen zusammen.",exampleSrc:"A: How many residents does the building have?\nB: Twelve parties.\nA: Does everyone know each other?\nB: Most of them, yes. We barbecue together.",funFact:"From 'bewohnen' (to inhabit). 'Die Bewohner des Hauses' (the residents of the building). The Be- prefix + wohnen makes it about who lives somewhere."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Bewohnerin",src:"the resident (female)",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Bewohner + -in. On official forms: 'Bewohner/Bewohnerin.'",example:"A: Sind Sie Bewohnerin dieses Hauses?\nB: Ja, seit f\u00fcnf Jahren.\nA: Dann kennen Sie sicher Frau Schmidt.\nB: Nat\u00fcrlich, sie wohnt \u00fcber mir.",exampleSrc:"A: Are you a resident of this building?\nB: Yes, for five years.\nA: Then you surely know Mrs. Schmidt.\nB: Of course, she lives above me.",funFact:"Female resident. On official forms: 'Bewohner/Bewohnerin' or the modern 'Bewohnende' (gender-neutral)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Mieter",src:"the tenant",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"From 'mieten' (to rent). Over 50% of Germans rent rather than own.",example:"A: Der Mieter im dritten Stock zieht aus.\nB: Schade, er war nett.\nA: Wer wird der neue Mieter?\nB: Keine Ahnung, aber die Nachfrage ist gro\u00df.",exampleSrc:"A: The tenant on the third floor is moving out.\nB: Too bad, he was nice.\nA: Who will be the new tenant?\nB: No idea, but demand is high.",funFact:"From 'mieten' (to rent). Germany is a nation of renters: over 50% of Germans rent rather than own their home. Der Mieter has strong legal protections."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"der Bauernhof",src:"the farm"},{trg:"der Bewohner",src:"the resident, the inhabitant"},{trg:"die Bewohnerin",src:"the resident (female)"},{trg:"der Mieter",src:"the tenant"}]},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Mieterin",src:"the tenant (female)",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Mieter + -in. German rental law is among the most tenant-friendly in the world.",example:"A: Die Mieterin hat sich beschwert.\nB: Wor\u00fcber?\nA: \u00dcber den L\u00e4rm vom Biergarten.\nB: Verst\u00e4ndlich, aber es ist Sommer!",exampleSrc:"A: The tenant complained.\nB: About what?\nA: About the noise from the beer garden.\nB: Understandable, but it is summer!",funFact:"Female tenant. German rental law (Mietrecht) is among the most tenant-friendly in the world. Evictions are difficult. Rent caps exist."},
{type:"fb",s:"Der {1} verkauft frischen Spargel direkt vom Feld.",a:["Bauer"],opts:["Bauer","Mieter","Bewohner","Bauernhof"],hint:"Which masculine noun means 'farmer,' from Old High German 'giburo' (neighbor)?",sSrc:"The farmer sells fresh asparagus straight from the field."},
{type:"mc",q:"Was ist ein Bauernhof?",opts:["ein Biergarten","eine Wohnung","ein Markt","eine Farm"],ans:"eine Farm",hint:"A compound of 'Bauer' and 'Hof.' An agricultural property where animals are raised and crops grown."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Haustier",src:"the pet",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"'Haus' (house) + 'Tier' (animal). Neuter because Tier is neuter.",example:"A: Hast du ein Haustier?\nB: Ja, eine Katze.\nA: Haustiere d\u00fcrfen in Bierg\u00e4rten meistens mit.\nB: Meine Katze bleibt lieber zu Hause.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you have a pet?\nB: Yes, a cat.\nA: Pets are usually allowed in beer gardens.\nB: My cat prefers to stay home.",funFact:"COMPOUND: Haus (house) + Tier (animal). 'Haus' (house) + 'Tier' (animal). Germans love their Haustiere: 34 million pets, more than in most European countries. Dogs can ride public transit."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Marille",src:"the apricot (Austrian)",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Austrian for 'Aprikose.' From Italian 'amarella' (little bitter one).",example:"A: In Wien sagt man Marille.\nB: Und in Berlin Aprikose.\nA: Marillenknödel sind österreichisch.\nB: Und unglaublich lecker!",exampleSrc:"A: In Vienna they say Marille.\nB: And in Berlin Aprikose.\nA: Apricot dumplings are Austrian.\nB: And incredibly delicious!",funFact:"Austrian for 'Aprikose' (apricot). From Italian 'amarella' (little bitter one). 'Marillenknödel' (apricot dumplings) are Austria's most famous dessert."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Paradeiser",src:"the tomato (Austrian)",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Austrian for 'Tomate.' From 'Paradiesapfel' (paradise apple).",example:"A: Gib mir bitte einen Paradeiser.\nB: Du meinst eine Tomate?\nA: In \u00d6sterreich sagen wir Paradeiser.\nB: Paradiesapfel, wie poetisch!",exampleSrc:"A: Please pass me a Paradeiser.\nB: You mean a tomato?\nA: In Austria we say Paradeiser.\nB: Paradise apple, how poetic!",funFact:"Austrian for 'Tomate.' From Italian 'pomodoro' (golden apple) via 'Paradiesapfel' (paradise apple). Austrians still call the tomato a 'paradise fruit.'"},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Erdapfel",src:"the potato (Austrian/Swiss)",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"'Erd' (earth) + 'Apfel' (apple). French says the same: 'pomme de terre.'",example:"A: Erdapfelsalat zum Schnitzel?\nB: Unbedingt! In \u00d6sterreich geh\u00f6rt das zusammen.\nA: Kartoffelsalat in Deutschland.\nB: Erdapfelsalat in Wien. Gleiches Gericht.",exampleSrc:"A: Potato salad with the schnitzel?\nB: Absolutely! In Austria they belong together.\nA: Kartoffelsalat in Germany.\nB: Erdapfelsalat in Vienna. Same dish.",funFact:"Austrian/Swiss for 'Kartoffel' (potato). 'Erd' (earth) + 'Apfel' (apple). An earth apple. French says the same: 'pomme de terre.' Three names for one vegetable."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Henderl",src:"the chicken (Austrian)",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"Austrian diminutive. The -erl suffix is the Austrian form of -chen.",example:"A: Ein halbes Henderl, bitte!\nB: Mit Kartoffelsalat?\nA: Nat\u00fcrlich!\nB: Kommt sofort.",exampleSrc:"A: Half a chicken, please!\nB: With potato salad?\nA: Of course!\nB: Coming right up.",funFact:"Austrian dialect for a small chicken. The -erl suffix is the Austrian diminutive (like -chen in standard German). 'Ein halbes Henderl' is a classic Austrian Gasthaus order."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"die Marille",src:"the apricot (Austrian)"},{trg:"der Paradeiser",src:"the tomato (Austrian)"},{trg:"der Erdapfel",src:"the potato (Austrian/Swiss)"},{trg:"das Henderl",src:"the chicken (Austrian)"}]},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Hendl",src:"the chicken (Bavarian)",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"Bavarian dialect. Even shorter than Henderl. Neuter because of the diminutive.",example:"A: Auf dem Oktoberfest gibt es Hendl.\nB: Hendl mit Kartoffelsalat!\nA: Das klassische Oktoberfest-Essen.\nB: Dazu eine Ma\u00df Bier.",exampleSrc:"A: At Oktoberfest there is chicken.\nB: Chicken with potato salad!\nA: The classic Oktoberfest meal.\nB: With a liter of beer.",funFact:"Bavarian dialect for chicken. Even shorter than Henderl. 'Hendl mit Kartoffelsalat' is the quintessential Oktoberfest meal."},
{type:"mc",q:"\u00dcber 50% der Deutschen wohnen zur Miete. Was ist ein 'Mieter'?",opts:["ein Bewohner, der kauft","ein Bauer","ein Bewohner, der mietet","ein Haustier"],ans:"ein Bewohner, der mietet",hint:"From 'mieten' (to rent). A person who pays rent rather than owning property."}
]},
{id:"deu_r18l6b",title:"Dialekt auf dem Teller (Teil 2)",icon:"\uD83C\uDDE6\uD83C\uDDF9",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Dialekt auf dem Teller (continued)",desc:"Continue practicing the vocabulary from this topic.",goals:["Review and practice key words"]},
{type:"fb",s:"In Bierg\u00e4rten sind Hunde willkommen. 'Hund' ist ein Haus{1}.",a:["tier"],opts:["tier","bauer","bewohner","mieter"],hint:"Which German word meaning 'animal' completes this compound noun?",sSrc:"Dogs are welcome in beer gardens. 'Hund' is a pet (house-animal)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Obers",src:"the cream (Austrian)",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"Austrian for 'Sahne.' From 'das Obere' (the top part) because cream rises to the top.",example:"A: Kaffee mit Obers, bitte.\nB: In Deutschland sagt man Sahne.\nA: Aber Obers klingt sch\u00f6ner.\nB: Finde ich auch!",exampleSrc:"A: Coffee with cream, please.\nB: In Germany they say Sahne.\nA: But Obers sounds nicer.\nB: I think so too!",funFact:"Austrian for 'Sahne' (cream). From 'das Obere' (the top part) because cream rises to the top of milk. 'Kaffee mit Obers' is how you order coffee with cream in Vienna."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Schwammerl",src:"the mushroom (Bavarian/Austrian)",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"The -erl diminutive. 'Schwammerlsuppe' (mushroom soup) is Bavarian comfort food.",example:"A: Gehen wir Schwammerl suchen!\nB: Im Wald? Ist das nicht gef\u00e4hrlich?\nA: Nicht, wenn man sich auskennt.\nB: Schwammerlsuppe w\u00e4re toll.",exampleSrc:"A: Let us go mushroom hunting!\nB: In the forest? Is that not dangerous?\nA: Not if you know what you are doing.\nB: Mushroom soup would be great.",funFact:"Bavarian/Austrian for 'Pilz' (mushroom). 'Schwammerlsuppe' (mushroom soup) is comfort food in Bavaria and Austria. Standard German 'Pilz' sounds clinical by comparison."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Fleischhauer",src:"the butcher (Austrian)",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"'Fleisch' (meat) + 'Hauer' (one who chops). The word paints a picture.",example:"A: Wo ist der n\u00e4chste Fleischhauer?\nB: In \u00d6sterreich sagt man Fleischhauer.\nA: In Deutschland Metzger oder Fleischer.\nB: Drei W\u00f6rter, ein Beruf.",exampleSrc:"A: Where is the nearest butcher?\nB: In Austria they say Fleischhauer.\nA: In Germany Metzger or Fleischer.\nB: Three words, one trade.",funFact:"Austrian for 'Metzger' (butcher). 'Fleisch' (meat) + 'Hauer' (one who chops). Standard German has Metzger (south) and Fleischer (north). Three words, one trade."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Backrohr",src:"the oven (Austrian)",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"'Back' (bake) + 'Rohr' (pipe/tube). The oven as a baking tube.",example:"A: Schieb den Kuchen ins Backrohr!\nB: Auf welcher Temperatur?\nA: 180 Grad, wie immer.\nB: In Deutschland sagt man Backofen.",exampleSrc:"A: Put the cake in the oven!\nB: At what temperature?\nA: 180 degrees, as always.\nB: In Germany they say Backofen.",funFact:"Austrian for 'Backofen' (oven). 'Back' (bake) + 'Rohr' (pipe/tube). The oven as a baking tube. Same appliance, Austrian name."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Br\u00f6tli",src:"the bread roll (Swiss)",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"Swiss diminutive. The -li suffix is the Swiss form of -chen.",example:"A: Ein Br\u00f6tli mit Butter, bitte.\nB: In Z\u00fcrich sagt man Br\u00f6tli.\nA: In Berlin Br\u00f6tchen, in M\u00fcnchen Semmel.\nB: Jede Region hat ihr eigenes Wort!",exampleSrc:"A: A bread roll with butter, please.\nB: In Zurich they say Br\u00f6tli.\nA: In Berlin Br\u00f6tchen, in Munich Semmel.\nB: Every region has its own word!",funFact:"Swiss German for 'Br\u00f6tchen' (bread roll). The -li suffix is the Swiss diminutive. Every German-speaking country has its own word for a bread roll."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"der Schwammerl",src:"the mushroom (Bavarian/Austrian)"},{trg:"der Fleischhauer",src:"the butcher (Austrian)"},{trg:"das Backrohr",src:"the oven (Austrian)"},{trg:"das Br\u00f6tli",src:"the bread roll (Swiss)"}]},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Glace",src:"the ice cream (Swiss)",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Swiss German for 'Eis.' From French 'glace' (ice). Shows French influence.",example:"A: M\u00f6chtest du eine Kugel Glace?\nB: In der Schweiz sagt man so.\nA: Eine Kugel Glace in Bern, eine Kugel Eis in Berlin.\nB: Hauptsache, es schmeckt!",exampleSrc:"A: Would you like a scoop of ice cream?\nB: In Switzerland they say it that way.\nA: A scoop of Glace in Bern, a scoop of Eis in Berlin.\nB: The main thing is it tastes good!",funFact:"Swiss German for 'Eis' (ice cream). From French 'glace' (ice). Switzerland's French influence shows in its food vocabulary."},
{type:"tip",title:"Drei L\u00e4nder, drei K\u00fcchen",text:"German is spoken in Germany, Austria, and Switzerland (plus Liechtenstein, Luxembourg, and parts of Belgium and Italy). Each country has unique food vocabulary.\n\nStandard German is understood everywhere, but regional terms carry identity:\n\nTomate (DE) = Paradeiser (AT)\nKartoffel (DE) = Erdapfel (AT/CH)\nSahne (DE) = Obers (AT)\nBr\u00f6tchen (DE) = Semmel (BY/AT) = Br\u00f6tli (CH)\nEis (DE) = Glace (CH)\nPilz (DE) = Schwammerl (BY/AT)\n\nThe Biergarten is Bavarian. The Beisl is Austrian. The Beiz is Swiss. Same concept: a place to eat, drink, and belong.",deepDive:"Knowing regional variants shows respect and cultural awareness. Austrian German (Österreichisches Deutsch) and Swiss Standard German (Schweizer Hochdeutsch) are officially recognized standard varieties, not dialects. They have their own dictionaries and official vocabulary lists."},
{type:"mc",q:"In \u00d6sterreich hei\u00dft 'Sahne' (cream) wie?",opts:["Obers","Br\u00f6tli","Glace","Paradeiser"],ans:"Obers",hint:"This word comes from 'das Obere' because cream rises to the top of the milk."},
{type:"fb",s:"In Wien bestellt man 'Kaffee mit {1}' statt 'Kaffee mit Sahne.'",a:["Obers"],opts:["Obers","Glace","Marille","Erdapfel"],hint:"The Austrian word for cream, from 'the top part' of milk.",sSrc:"In Vienna you order 'coffee with Obers' instead of 'coffee with Sahne.'"},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"Marille",src:"Aprikose"},{trg:"Paradeiser",src:"Tomate"},{trg:"Erdapfel",src:"Kartoffel"},{trg:"Schwammerl",src:"Pilz"}]},
{type:"mc",q:"'Die Bewohner warten _____ den Fr\u00fchling.' Welche Pr\u00e4position erg\u00e4nzt 'warten'?",opts:["auf","f\u00fcr","\u00fcber","an"],ans:"auf",hint:"Warten always pairs with this preposition. You wait ON something."},
{type:"mc",q:"'_____ ich in Wien war, habe ich zum ersten Mal Marillenkn\u00f6del probiert.'",opts:["Wenn","Damit","Weil","Als"],ans:"Als",hint:"Being in Vienna was a specific trip in the past. One time."},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'der Fleischhauer'?",opts:["the chicken (Austrian)","the tomato (Austrian)","the tenant","the butcher (Austrian)"],ans:"the butcher (Austrian)",hint:"Fleisch (meat) + Hauer (chopper). Regional word for someone who cuts and sells meat."},
{type:"fb",s:"Wie sagt man 'the oven (Austrian)' auf Deutsch? {1}",a:["das Backrohr"],opts:["das Hendl","die Bewohnerin","der Mieter","das Backrohr"],hint:"Back- (baking) + Rohr (pipe/tube). Austrian word for the kitchen appliance that bakes.",sSrc:"How do you say 'the oven (Austrian)' in German?"}
]},

// ─── Lesson 7: Prost und Wiederholung ───────────────────────────────
{id:"deu_r18l7",title:"Prost und Wiederholung",icon:"\uD83C\uDF7B",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Prost und Wiederholung",desc:"Time to prove your skills. Review all Unit 18 grammar, vocabulary, and cultural knowledge in a comprehensive assessment.",goals:["Test als vs wenn in varied contexts","Prove mastery of verbs with fixed prepositions","Use da-/wo- compounds fluently"]},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Abt",src:"the abbot",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"From Latin 'abbas.' Many German breweries were founded by monks.",example:"A: Der Abt leitete das Kloster.\nB: Und die Brauerei!\nA: Klosterbier hat eine lange Tradition.\nB: Manche Kl\u00f6ster brauen noch heute.",exampleSrc:"A: The abbot led the monastery.\nB: And the brewery!\nA: Monastery beer has a long tradition.\nB: Some monasteries still brew today.",funFact:"From Latin 'abbas.' Many German breweries were founded by monks, and the Abt supervised beer production. 'Klosterbier' (monastery beer) has a centuries-old tradition."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Abwart",src:"the caretaker (Swiss)",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Swiss German for 'Hausmeister.' 'Ab' (away) + 'Wart' (one who watches).",example:"A: Der Abwart k\u00fcmmert sich um das Geb\u00e4ude.\nB: In Deutschland sagt man Hausmeister.\nA: In der Schweiz ist es der Abwart.\nB: Wieder ein regionales Wort!",exampleSrc:"A: The caretaker takes care of the building.\nB: In Germany they say Hausmeister.\nA: In Switzerland it is the Abwart.\nB: Another regional word!",funFact:"Swiss German for 'Hausmeister' (caretaker/janitor). 'Ab' (away) + 'Wart' (one who watches). The person who watches over a building."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Abwartin",src:"the caretaker (female, Swiss)",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Abwart + -in. Swiss German follows the same -in pattern for feminine forms.",example:"A: Die Abwartin hat den Flur geputzt.\nB: Sie macht das jeden Morgen.\nA: In der Schweiz sagt man Abwartin.\nB: Und in Deutschland Hausmeisterin.",exampleSrc:"A: The caretaker cleaned the hallway.\nB: She does that every morning.\nA: In Switzerland they say Abwartin.\nB: And in Germany Hausmeisterin.",funFact:"Female caretaker. Swiss German follows the same -in pattern for feminine forms as standard German."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Bub",src:"the boy (Bavarian/Austrian/Swiss)",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Southern German for 'Junge.' Used across all southern German-speaking regions.",example:"A: Der Bub spielt im Garten.\nB: In Bayern sagt man Bub.\nA: In Norddeutschland sagt man Junge.\nB: Nord-S\u00fcd-Unterschied, wie immer.",exampleSrc:"A: The boy is playing in the garden.\nB: In Bavaria they say Bub.\nA: In northern Germany they say Junge.\nB: North-south difference, as always.",funFact:"Bavarian/Austrian/Swiss for 'Junge' (boy). 'Ein lieber Bub.' In northern Germany, nobody says Bub. Another north-south divide."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Feber",src:"February (Austrian)",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Austrian for 'Februar.' Shortened, localized. Instantly marks someone as Austrian.",example:"A: Im Feber ist es kalt in Wien.\nB: Feber? Du meinst Februar?\nA: In \u00d6sterreich sagen wir Feber.\nB: Wieder was gelernt!",exampleSrc:"A: In Feber it is cold in Vienna.\nB: Feber? You mean February?\nA: In Austria we say Feber.\nB: Learned something new!",funFact:"Austrian for 'Februar.' One of those calendar words that instantly tells you someone is Austrian."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"der Abwart",src:"the caretaker (Swiss)"},{trg:"die Abwartin",src:"the caretaker (female, Swiss)"},{trg:"der Bub",src:"the boy (Bavarian/Austrian/Swiss)"},{trg:"der Feber",src:"February (Austrian)"}]},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Poulet",src:"the chicken (Swiss)",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"From French 'poulet.' Switzerland's French influence again.",example:"A: Poulet mit Pommes, bitte.\nB: In Z\u00fcrich sagt man Poulet.\nA: In Berlin H\u00e4hnchen, in M\u00fcnchen Hendl.\nB: Drei L\u00e4nder, drei H\u00fchner!",exampleSrc:"A: Chicken with fries, please.\nB: In Zurich they say Poulet.\nA: In Berlin H\u00e4hnchen, in Munich Hendl.\nB: Three countries, three chickens!",funFact:"Swiss German for 'H\u00e4hnchen' (chicken). From French 'poulet.' 'Poulet mit Pommes' in Zurich = 'H\u00e4hnchen mit Pommes' in Berlin = 'Hendl mit Pommes' in Munich."},
{type:"fb",s:"In der Schweiz sagt man nicht 'Hausmeister,' sondern {1}.",a:["Abwart"],opts:["Abwart","Bub","Feber","Abt"],hint:"The Swiss German word for caretaker, from 'ab' (away) + 'Wart' (watcher).",sSrc:"In Switzerland they do not say 'Hausmeister' but 'Abwart.'"},
{type:"mc",q:"In \u00d6sterreich hei\u00dft der Monat Februar wie?",opts:["Abwart","Bub","Feber","Poulet"],ans:"Feber",hint:"The shortened Austrian version of the Latin month name. Instantly identifies someone as Austrian."},
{type:"teach",trg:"ein paar",src:"a few, some",pos:"pron",gender:null,note:"Written lowercase. 'Ein Paar' (capitalized) = a pair/couple. Case matters!",example:"A: Ich brauche ein paar Minuten.\nB: Kein Problem, nimm dir Zeit.\nA: Ein paar Freunde kommen sp\u00e4ter.\nB: Je mehr, desto besser!",exampleSrc:"A: I need a few minutes.\nB: No problem, take your time.\nA: A few friends are coming later.\nB: The more, the merrier!",funFact:"Written lowercase (unlike 'ein Paar' = a pair/couple). 'Ein paar Freunde' = a few friends. 'Ein Paar Schuhe' = a pair of shoes. The capital P changes the meaning entirely."},
{type:"teach",trg:"halt",src:"just, simply (particle)",pos:"part",gender:null,note:"'Das ist halt so.' Extremely common in spoken German, especially southern.",example:"A: Warum regnet es so viel?\nB: Das ist halt Sommer in Berlin.\nA: Ich wollte im Biergarten sitzen.\nB: Dann musst du halt warten.",exampleSrc:"A: Why does it rain so much?\nB: That is just how summer is in Berlin.\nA: I wanted to sit in the beer garden.\nB: Then you just have to wait.",funFact:"A particle meaning 'just, simply.' 'Das ist halt so' (That is just how it is). Extremely common in spoken German, especially southern. Signals acceptance or resignation."},
{type:"teach",trg:"extra",src:"extra, on purpose, especially",pos:"adv",gender:null,note:"Same as English. Also means 'on purpose': 'Das hast du extra gemacht!'",example:"A: Ich habe extra f\u00fcr dich Spargel gekauft.\nB: Wie nett von dir!\nA: Der letzte der Saison.\nB: Extra f\u00fcr mich? Danke!",exampleSrc:"A: I bought asparagus especially for you.\nB: How nice of you!\nA: The last of the season.\nB: Especially for me? Thanks!",funFact:"Same as English 'extra.' Also means 'on purpose': 'Das hast du extra gemacht!' (You did that on purpose!)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"gratis",src:"free (of charge)",pos:"adv",gender:null,note:"From Latin 'gratis.' Also 'kostenlos' or 'umsonst.'",example:"A: Ist der Eintritt gratis?\nB: Ja, der Biergarten ist frei zug\u00e4nglich.\nA: Und das Wasser?\nB: Auch gratis, zum Bier dazu.",exampleSrc:"A: Is admission free?\nB: Yes, the beer garden is freely accessible.\nA: And the water?\nB: Also free, with the beer.",funFact:"From Latin 'gratis' (for free). 'Der Eintritt ist gratis.' Germans also say 'kostenlos' (costless) or 'umsonst' (for nothing)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"jedes Mal",src:"every time",pos:"adv",gender:null,note:"'Jedes' (every) + 'Mal' (time). Perfect with 'wenn' for repeated actions.",example:"A: Jedes Mal, wenn ich hier bin, bestelle ich Spargel.\nB: Du bist wie Heinrich!\nA: Jedes Mal schmeckt es anders.\nB: Das macht es spannend.",exampleSrc:"A: Every time I am here, I order asparagus.\nB: You are like Heinrich!\nA: Every time it tastes different.\nB: That makes it exciting.",funFact:"'Jedes' (every) + 'Mal' (time/instance). 'Jedes Mal, wenn ich im Biergarten bin, bestelle ich Spargel.' Perfect with 'wenn' for repeated actions."},
{type:"mc",q:"Das ist halt so. Was bedeutet 'halt' in diesem Satz?",opts:["Stopp! Halt!","einfach, eben","sehr langsam","sehr schnell"],ans:"einfach, eben",hint:"A common spoken particle meaning 'just' or 'simply,' signaling acceptance."}
]},
{id:"deu_r18l7b",title:"Prost und Wiederholung (Teil 2)",icon:"\uD83C\uDF7B",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Prost und Wiederholung (continued)",desc:"Continue practicing the vocabulary from this topic.",goals:["Review and practice key words"]},
{type:"fb",s:"Der Eintritt zum Biergarten ist {1}. Man braucht nichts zu bezahlen.",a:["gratis"],opts:["gratis","extra","halt","nebenbei"],hint:"A Latin word meaning 'free of charge,' synonymous with 'kostenlos.'",sSrc:"Admission to the beer garden is free. You do not need to pay anything."},
{type:"teach",trg:"nebenbei",src:"on the side, incidentally, by the way",pos:"adv",gender:null,note:"'Neben' (beside) + 'bei' (by). A useful conversational filler.",example:"A: Nebenbei bemerkt, der Spargel war fantastisch.\nB: Finde ich auch!\nA: Und nebenbei: Lukas hat toll gespielt.\nB: Ja, wirklich beeindruckend.",exampleSrc:"A: By the way, the asparagus was fantastic.\nB: I think so too!\nA: And incidentally: Lukas played great.\nB: Yes, really impressive.",funFact:"'Neben' (beside) + 'bei' (by). 'Nebenbei bemerkt...' (By the way...). Also 'nebenbei arbeiten' (to work on the side). A useful conversational filler."},
{type:"teach",trg:"au",src:"ouch, ow",pos:"intj",gender:null,note:"An exclamation of pain or surprise. Short for 'Aua!' Also a place name element.",example:"A: Au! Das war hei\u00df!\nB: Vorsicht mit dem Grill!\nA: Au, mein Finger!\nB: Zeig mal, ist es schlimm?",exampleSrc:"A: Ouch! That was hot!\nB: Careful with the grill!\nA: Ow, my finger!\nB: Let me see, is it bad?",funFact:"An exclamation of pain or surprise. 'Au! Das war hei\u00df!' Short for 'Aua!' Also a place name element: 'Au' means a water meadow."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Blitz",src:"the lightning, the flash",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Also 'Blitzkrieg' (lightning war), 'Blitzeis' (flash ice). Fast and sudden.",example:"A: Hast du den Blitz gesehen?\nB: Ja! Und dann der Donner!\nA: Ein Gewitter im Biergarten.\nB: Schnell, unter das Dach!",exampleSrc:"A: Did you see the lightning?\nB: Yes! And then the thunder!\nA: A thunderstorm in the beer garden.\nB: Quick, under the roof!",funFact:"Same word as English 'blitz.' 'Blitzschnell' (lightning fast), 'Blitzeis' (flash ice on roads). Also the camera flash. Germans say 'Blitz' when a summer storm interrupts a Biergarten evening."},
{type:"mc",q:"'Jedes Mal, _____ wir im Biergarten sind, bestellt Hildi Spargel.' Welches Wort passt?",opts:["obwohl","als","wenn","weil"],ans:"wenn",hint:"'Jedes Mal' signals repetition. Which 'when' word is for repeated events?"},
{type:"mc",q:"Heinrich _____ auf frischem Spargel zum Mittagessen.",opts:["denkt","freut sich","wartet","besteht"],ans:"besteht",hint:"Which verb means 'to insist' and pairs with 'auf'?"},
{type:"fb",s:"Mia interessiert sich f\u00fcr Bio-Essen. Sie interessiert sich {1}.",a:["daf\u00fcr"],opts:["daf\u00fcr","darauf","dar\u00fcber","daran"],hint:"The fixed preposition is F\u00dcR. Replace the prepositional phrase with da- plus the preposition.",sSrc:"Mia is interested in organic food. She is interested in it."},
{type:"mc",q:"Du willst fragen 'Wor\u00fcber freust du dich?' Was bedeutet das auf Englisch?",opts:["What are you waiting for?","What are you thinking of?","What are you interested in?","What are you happy about?"],ans:"What are you happy about?",hint:"The wo-compound wo + \u00fcber asks regarding the topic of a feeling. Which preposition does 'sich freuen' pair with for current feelings?"},
{type:"drag_fill",s:"{1} ich zum ersten Mal Spargel a\u00df, freute ich mich {2}. Jetzt freue ich mich {3} Mal {4}.",blanks:{"1":"Als","2":"dar\u00fcber","3":"jedes","4":"darauf"},pool:["Als","Wenn","dar\u00fcber","darauf","daran","jedes","jede","daf\u00fcr"],hint:"First: one-time past event. Second: happy ABOUT it (past, da + \u00fcber). Third + fourth: every time, looking forward to it (future, da + auf).",sSrc:"When I ate asparagus for the first time, I was happy about it. Now I look forward to it every time."},
{type:"mc",q:"'Poulet' ist das Schweizer Wort f\u00fcr...",opts:["H\u00e4hnchen","Schweinefleisch","Rindfleisch","Lamm"],ans:"H\u00e4hnchen",hint:"This word comes from French and refers to poultry."},
{type:"fb",s:"Der Eintritt zum Biergarten ist {1}. Man muss nichts bezahlen.",a:["gratis"],opts:["gratis","extra","halt","nebenbei"],hint:"A word from Latin meaning 'for free.'",sSrc:"Admission to the beer garden is free. You do not have to pay anything."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"Als ich ankam",src:"When I arrived (one time)"},{trg:"Wenn ich esse",src:"When(ever) I eat"},{trg:"sich freuen auf",src:"to look forward to"},{trg:"Worauf wartest du?",src:"What are you waiting for?"}]},
{type:"mc",q:"'_____ wartet Verumius?' -- 'Auf den Kellner. Er wartet _____.'",opts:["Worauf...darauf","Woran...daran","Wof\u00fcr...daf\u00fcr","Wor\u00fcber...dar\u00fcber"],ans:"Worauf...darauf",hint:"'Warten AUF' is the fixed combo. Question = wo + auf. Answer = da + auf."},
{type:"drag_fill",s:"{1} wir im Biergarten sa\u00dfen, rief Heinrich an. Er bestand {2}, dass wir Spargel bestellen.",blanks:{"1":"Als","2":"darauf"},pool:["Als","Wenn","darauf","dar\u00fcber","daran","Weil"],hint:"First blank: one specific past moment (als vs. wenn). Second blank: bestehen takes a fixed preposition. Replace 'auf etwas' with the da-compound.",sSrc:"When we were sitting in the beer garden, Heinrich called. He insisted that we order asparagus."},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'au'?",opts:["every time","ouch, ow","the caretaker (Swiss)","on the side, incidentally, by the way"],ans:"ouch, ow",hint:"A short exclamation of pain. Universal across German dialects. Think: stubbing your toe."},
{type:"fb",s:"Wie sagt man 'the lightning, the flash' auf Deutsch? {1}",a:["der Blitz"],opts:["halt","der Blitz","der Abwart","der Abt"],hint:"The bright flash in the sky during a storm. Also appears in compound words for speed.",sSrc:"How do you say 'the lightning, the flash' in German?"}
]},

// ─── Lesson 8: Der Nachhauseweg ─────────────────────────────────────
{id:"deu_r18l8",title:"Der Nachhauseweg",icon:"\uD83C\uDF19",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Der Nachhauseweg",desc:"Berlin summer night. The group walks home together, splitting off one by one. Final vocabulary, final grammar assessment, and a moment of belonging.",goals:["Learn remaining vocabulary for food, farming, and daily life","Master all three grammar constructs in combination","Reflect on friendship and belonging"]},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Metzger",src:"the butcher",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Standard southern German. Northern: 'Fleischer.' Austrian: 'Fleischhauer.' Three words, one trade.",example:"A: Ich gehe zum Metzger.\nB: Bring bitte Bratwurst mit!\nA: Vom Metzger oder vom Supermarkt?\nB: Vom Metzger, die schmeckt besser.",exampleSrc:"A: I am going to the butcher.\nB: Please bring bratwurst!\nA: From the butcher or the supermarket?\nB: From the butcher, it tastes better.",funFact:"Standard southern German. Northern Germans say 'Fleischer,' Austrians say 'Fleischhauer.' From Latin 'macellarius' (slaughterer). Every region defends its word."},
{type:"teach",trg:"ern\u00e4hren",src:"to nourish, to feed",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Reflexive: 'sich ern\u00e4hren' (to eat, to sustain oneself). From 'Nahrung.'",example:"A: Wie ern\u00e4hrst du dich?\nB: Ich ern\u00e4hre mich meistens vegetarisch.\nA: Das ist gesund.\nB: Und gut f\u00fcr die Umwelt.",exampleSrc:"A: How do you eat?\nB: I eat mostly vegetarian.\nA: That is healthy.\nB: And good for the environment.",funFact:"Reflexive: 'sich ern\u00e4hren' (to eat, to sustain oneself). 'Sich gesund ern\u00e4hren' (to eat healthily). The er- prefix makes it about achieving nourishment."},
{type:"teach",trg:"fressen",src:"to eat (for animals)",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Using 'fressen' for a person is rude. Humans 'essen,' animals 'fressen.'",example:"A: Die Katze frisst ihr Futter.\nB: Sie frisst immer so schnell.\nA: Sag nie 'fressen' \u00fcber einen Menschen!\nB: Warum nicht?\nA: Das ist sehr unhöflich.",exampleSrc:"A: The cat eats its food.\nB: She always eats so fast.\nA: Never say 'fressen' about a person!\nB: Why not?\nA: That is very rude.",funFact:"To eat (for animals). 'Der Hund frisst.' Using 'fressen' for a person is rude: 'Er frisst wie ein Schwein' (He eats like a pig). The distinction matters."},
{type:"teach",trg:"f\u00fcttern",src:"to feed (an animal or baby)",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"From 'Futter' (animal food/feed). 'Die Enten f\u00fcttern' (to feed the ducks).",example:"A: D\u00fcrfen wir die Enten f\u00fcttern?\nB: Ja, aber nur mit Haferflocken.\nA: Kein Brot?\nB: Nein, Brot ist schlecht f\u00fcr Enten.",exampleSrc:"A: Can we feed the ducks?\nB: Yes, but only with oat flakes.\nA: No bread?\nB: No, bread is bad for ducks.",funFact:"From 'Futter' (animal food/feed). Also slang: 'Ich muss meinen Computer f\u00fcttern' (I need to feed data into my computer)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"grillieren",src:"to barbecue (Swiss)",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Swiss German for 'grillen.' The -ieren suffix shows French influence.",example:"A: Wollen wir am Wochenende grillieren?\nB: In der Schweiz sagt man grillieren.\nA: In Deutschland grillen.\nB: Gleicher Rauch, anderes Verb!",exampleSrc:"A: Shall we barbecue this weekend?\nB: In Switzerland they say grillieren.\nA: In Germany grillen.\nB: Same smoke, different verb!",funFact:"Swiss German for 'grillen.' The -ieren suffix shows French influence. In Switzerland: 'Wir grillieren am See.' In Germany: 'Wir grillen im Park.'"},
{type:"fb",s:"Der {1} verkauft frische Bratwurst. Dort schmeckt sie am besten.",a:["Metzger"],opts:["Metzger","Koch","Bauer","Kellner"],hint:"The southern German word for a butcher, from Latin 'macellarius.'",sSrc:"The butcher sells fresh bratwurst. There it tastes best."},
{type:"mc",q:"Wie ern\u00e4hrst du dich? -- Ich ern\u00e4hre mich vegetarisch. Was bedeutet 'sich ern\u00e4hren'?",opts:["to cook","to nourish yourself, to eat","to feed an animal","to cater for guests"],ans:"to nourish yourself, to eat",hint:"A reflexive verb describing how you sustain your body through food, from 'Nahrung.'"},
{type:"teach",trg:"n\u00e4hen",src:"to sew",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"From Old High German 'najen.' Related to English 'needle.'",example:"A: Kannst du n\u00e4hen?\nB: Ja, ich n\u00e4he meine Kn\u00f6pfe selbst an.\nA: Ich brauche eine N\u00e4hmaschine.\nB: F\u00fcr gro\u00dfe Projekte lohnt sich das.",exampleSrc:"A: Can you sew?\nB: Yes, I sew my own buttons on.\nA: I need a sewing machine.\nB: For big projects it is worth it.",funFact:"To sew. From Old High German 'najen.' Related to English 'needle' through the same root. 'Mit hei\u00dfer Nadel gen\u00e4ht' (sewn with a hot needle) means done hastily."},
{type:"teach",trg:"n\u00fctzen",src:"to be useful, to use",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Southern/Austrian variant of 'nutzen.' Both are correct.",example:"A: Das n\u00fctzt nichts.\nB: Doch, es n\u00fctzt mehr als du denkst.\nA: In \u00d6sterreich sagt man n\u00fctzen.\nB: In Deutschland auch nutzen.",exampleSrc:"A: That is no use.\nB: Yes it is, it helps more than you think.\nA: In Austria they say n\u00fctzen.\nB: In Germany also nutzen.",funFact:"Southern German and Austrian variant of 'nutzen.' Both are correct. The \u00fc vs u distinction is regional, not grammatical."},
{type:"teach",trg:"nutzen",src:"to use, to make use of",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Standard German variant. 'Die Gelegenheit nutzen' (to seize the opportunity).",example:"A: Nutze die Gelegenheit!\nB: Welche Gelegenheit?\nA: Der letzte Spargel der Saison!\nB: Du hast recht, ich nutze sie.",exampleSrc:"A: Seize the opportunity!\nB: Which opportunity?\nA: The last asparagus of the season!\nB: You are right, I will seize it.",funFact:"'Die Gelegenheit nutzen' (to seize the opportunity). 'Nutzen' as a noun (der Nutzen) means benefit. Verb and noun share the same form."},
{type:"teach",trg:"runterwerfen",src:"to throw down",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"'Runter' (down) + 'werfen' (to throw). Separable. Colloquial contraction of 'herunterwerfen.'",example:"A: Wirf das nicht runter!\nB: Entschuldigung, es ist mir aus der Hand gerutscht.\nA: Der Bierkrug ist fast runtergefallen.\nB: Zum Gl\u00fcck nicht!",exampleSrc:"A: Do not throw that down!\nB: Sorry, it slipped out of my hand.\nA: The beer stein almost fell down.\nB: Luckily not!",funFact:"'Runter' (down) + 'werfen' (to throw). Separable. Colloquial contraction of 'herunterwerfen.' Spoken German loves shortening."},
{type:"mc",q:"Tiere 'fressen.' Menschen 'essen.' Was ist der Unterschied?",opts:["Fressen ist h\u00f6flich","Fressen ist f\u00fcr Tiere","Essen ist f\u00fcr Tiere","Es gibt keinen Unterschied (nein)"],ans:"Fressen ist f\u00fcr Tiere",hint:"German has two verbs for eating. One is for animals, one is for humans. Calling a person by the animal word is a serious insult."},
{type:"mc",q:"Wirf das nicht ___! Es ist mir aus der Hand gerutscht.",opts:["rauf","rein","runter","raus"],ans:"runter",hint:"The colloquial prefix meaning downward. The opposite of rauf. A shortened form used in everyday spoken German."}
]},
{id:"deu_r18l8b",title:"Der Nachhauseweg (Teil 2)",icon:"\uD83C\uDF19",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Der Nachhauseweg (continued)",desc:"Continue practicing the vocabulary from this topic.",goals:["Review and practice key words"]},
{type:"fb",s:"In der Schweiz sagt man nicht 'grillen,' sondern {1}.",a:["grillieren"],opts:["grillieren","n\u00e4hen","n\u00fctzen","f\u00fcttern"],hint:"The Swiss verb for barbecuing, with the French-influenced -ieren suffix.",sSrc:"In Switzerland they do not say 'grillen' but 'grillieren.'"},
{type:"teach",trg:"verpflegen",src:"to cater, to provide food and care",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"From 'Pflege' (care) + ver- prefix. 'Die G\u00e4ste verpflegen.'",example:"A: Wer verpflegt die G\u00e4ste heute?\nB: Der Koch und seine K\u00f6chin.\nA: Die Verpflegung war ausgezeichnet.\nB: Ja, alles frisch und lecker.",exampleSrc:"A: Who caters for the guests today?\nB: The chef and his cook.\nA: The catering was excellent.\nB: Yes, everything fresh and delicious.",funFact:"From 'Pflege' (care) + ver- prefix. 'Verpflegung' (catering/provisions) appears on conference schedules. The word covers providing complete food and care."},
{type:"teach",trg:"bio-",src:"organic, biological (prefix)",pos:"part",gender:null,note:"Prefix meaning organic. 'Bio-Markt,' 'Bio-Bauer,' 'Bio-Milch.' Legally protected in the EU.",example:"A: Kaufst du im Bio-Markt ein?\nB: Ja, meistens Bio-Gem\u00fcse.\nA: Bio-Produkte sind teurer.\nB: Aber die Qualit\u00e4t lohnt sich.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you shop at the organic market?\nB: Yes, mostly organic vegetables.\nA: Organic products are more expensive.\nB: But the quality is worth it.",funFact:"Prefix meaning organic or biological. In German, bio- attaches to almost any food noun. The prefix alone on a label means certified organic under EU regulation."},
{type:"teach",trg:"einzel-",src:"single, individual (prefix)",pos:"part",gender:null,note:"'Einzelzimmer' (single room), 'Einzelkind' (only child), 'Einzelhandel' (retail).",example:"A: Ich brauche ein Einzelzimmer.\nB: F\u00fcr wie viele N\u00e4chte?\nA: Drei. Und bitte kein Einzelkind-Zuschlag.\nB: Kein Problem!",exampleSrc:"A: I need a single room.\nB: For how many nights?\nA: Three. And please no single supplement.\nB: No problem!",funFact:"Prefix meaning single or individual. 'Einzelzimmer' (single room), 'Einzelkind' (only child), 'Einzelhandel' (retail). One of German's most productive compound prefixes."},
{type:"mc",q:"'_____ Verumius nach Berlin kam, kannte er niemanden.' Welches Wort?",opts:["Wenn","Weil","Als","Obwohl"],ans:"Als",hint:"Arriving in Berlin was a single event in the past."},
{type:"mc",q:"Lukas freut sich dar\u00fcber, dass seine Freunde zugeh\u00f6rt haben. Was ersetzt 'dar\u00fcber'?",opts:["f\u00fcr + die Tatsache, dass sie zugeh\u00f6rt haben","\u00fcber + die Tatsache, dass sie zugeh\u00f6rt haben","auf + die Tatsache, dass sie zugeh\u00f6rt haben","an + die Tatsache, dass sie zugeh\u00f6rt haben (formal)"],ans:"\u00fcber + die Tatsache, dass sie zugeh\u00f6rt haben",hint:"The da-compound here uses the same preposition that 'sich freuen' takes when expressing a current emotion rather than anticipation."},
{type:"fb",s:"{1} besteht Heinrich? -- Darauf, dass wir Spargel bestellen.",a:["Worauf"],opts:["Worauf","Wor\u00fcber","Woran","Wof\u00fcr"],hint:"Bestehen AUF. The question form uses wo + auf.",sSrc:"What does Heinrich insist on? -- That we order asparagus."},
{type:"drag_fill",s:"{1} wir im Biergarten waren, freute sich Hildi {2}. Sie hatte sich lange {3} gefreut.",blanks:{"1":"Als","2":"dar\u00fcber","3":"darauf"},pool:["Als","Wenn","dar\u00fcber","darauf","daran","daf\u00fcr"],hint:"First: specific past evening (als). Second: happy ABOUT the evening (da + \u00fcber). Third: had looked FORWARD to it (da + auf).",sSrc:"When we were in the beer garden, Hildi was happy about it. She had looked forward to it for a long time."},
{type:"mc",q:"Welcher reflexive Ausdruck beschreibt gesundes, bewusstes Essen, im Gegensatz zum tierischen 'fressen'?",opts:["sich ern\u00e4hren","fressen","verpflegen","f\u00fcttern"],ans:"sich ern\u00e4hren",hint:"This reflexive verb is about sustained, healthy eating. Not for animals."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"als",src:"when (one-time past)"},{trg:"wenn",src:"when(ever) / if"},{trg:"darauf",src:"on it (da + auf)"},{trg:"Worauf?",src:"On what? (wo + auf)"}]},
{type:"mc",q:"Hildi sagt: 'Jedes Mal, _____ die Spargelzeit beginnt, denke ich _____ meine Kindheit.'",opts:["als...\u00fcber","wenn...auf","als...an","wenn...an"],ans:"wenn...an",hint:"Every year = repeated (conditional conjunction). Thinking OF something = denken + a fixed preposition."},
{type:"drag_fill",s:"Verumius wartet {1} den Fr\u00fchling. Er freut sich {2}.",blanks:{"1":"auf","2":"darauf"},pool:["auf","darauf","\u00fcber","dar\u00fcber","an","daran"],hint:"Warten AUF. Then replace 'auf den Fr\u00fchling' with the da-compound.",sSrc:"Verumius waits for spring. He looks forward to it."},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'bio-'?",opts:["organic, biological (prefix)","to eat (for animals)","to feed (an animal or baby)","to use, to make use of"],ans:"organic, biological (prefix)",hint:"From Greek 'bios' (life). In German supermarkets, it labels natural/pesticide-free products."},
{type:"fb",s:"Wie sagt man 'single, individual (prefix)' auf Deutsch? {1}",a:["einzel-"],opts:["einzel-","f\\u00fcttern","ern\\u00e4hren","n\\u00fctzen"],hint:"From 'ein' (one). A prefix meaning one at a time, separate, not in a group.",sSrc:"How do you say 'single, individual (prefix)' in German?"}
]}

]};

export default UNIT_18;
